  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ;; WEAVE 0.75 — active doctrine
  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  :section-1-what-weave-is
  """
  Weave = the POST-SFT finishing procedure for a Motoi generation.
  Applied to a fully-trained SFT adapter to raise ship-blocker scores
  (safety, circular-trap, lang-resistance) without corrupting the SFT
  substrate.

  What it IS NOT:
    · Not additional SFT training on new pairs (that's a new generation)
    · Not a corpus rebuild (that's substrate work)
    · Not RLHF from scratch (no infra + Alfred's no-external-corpora rule
      kills the reward model)

  Rename provenance:
    Grand Weave 1.0 (2026-07-17) was LIMA-centric. Mk A polish following
    that recipe REGRESSED circular-trap 20→5% and lang-resistance 93→60%.
    arXiv:2410.10862 (Superficial Safety Alignment Hypothesis, Oct 2024)
    documents WHY: at 1.5B scale, safety lives in a sparse SCU controller
    that a LIMA gradient overwrites. Weave 0.75 reorders the sequence to
    try training-free techniques FIRST, escalating to gradient-based only
    if the earlier steps don't clear ship-blockers.
  """

  :section-2-when-to-apply
  """
  SFT has completed and passed initial eval.
  Base SFT adapter is archived (immutable — every Weave step forks).
  Eval scores available for the SFT baseline (measure delta).
  Ship-blocker categories identified.

  NEVER apply Weave to an untested SFT — nothing to compare against.
  """

  :section-3-sequence
  """
  Full Weave pipeline for a generation (e.g. Mk 2). Order matters.
  Phase 0 (CPT) is the KNOWLEDGE-INJECTION layer; Phase 1 (SFT) is
  the SHAPE-RETRIEVAL layer; Phases 2-4 are finishing moves that
  fork from the SFT adapter.

    Phase 0: CPT (continuous pretraining, multi-shape)
        24-shape catalog per material type — see
        § section-cpt-shapes-catalog below. Reference + books +
        prose + graphs all fold as continuation text with M≈5
        paraphrases per shape. Ovadia (arXiv:2312.05934) + Physics
        3.1 (arXiv:2309.14316) — canonical-only = 0% extraction;
        multi-shape = 96.6% QA.
        eval → CPT knowledge probe (fact recall + reversal)
      │
    Phase 1: SFT (6 book-type templates + reference templates)
        Extract pairs per § section-authoring-templates-book-types.
        Preflight + fold + train. Archive immutable adapter.
        eval → 284-prompt harness
      │
      ├─ Phase 2: Spectral Surgery (training-free SVD reweighting)
      │       eval → won? cascade | no? revert
      ├─ Phase 3: LASER (layer-selective rank reduction, zero data)
      │       eval → won? cascade | no? revert
      └─ Phase 4: KTO with safety-heavy desirable set
              eval → won? ship candidate | no? intercept layer takes over

  Between each transition: rerun the 284-prompt eval + relevant
  probes. If a phase doesn't net-improve across ship-blocker
  categories, revert.

  Load-bearing rule: SFT CANNOT inject knowledge that CPT hasn't
  already presented in multiple shapes. If Mk 1's confabulation
  problem persists after Mk 2 SFT, that's evidence the CPT layer
  is missing shape diversity, not that SFT needs more pairs. Fix
  the CPT catalog first.

  Alfred (verbatim 2026-07-20): 'we test after the spectral
  surgery.' Applies to every phase: test after each move, decide
  next. Also 2026-07-20: 'CPT shapes will inform pedagogy.' —
  the audit tests whether books cover the shapes for their type.
  """

  :section-4-step-1-spectral-surgery
  """
  Cite: arXiv:2603.03995 (2026).

  Mechanism. SVD-decompose the LoRA adapter's low-rank matrices. Rescale
  singular values based on their contribution to a small CALIBRATION SET
  of target-behavior prompts. High-contribution directions amplified;
  low-contribution shrunk or zeroed. Training-free.

  Inputs:
    · SFT adapter at
      ~/.forge/runs/motoi-mk1/_archive/mk1-sft-final-20260720.safetensors
    · Calibration set: 100-500 prompts covering ship-blocker categories
      (safety-crisis, safety-emergency, circular-trap, lang-resistance).
      MUST be authored fresh; must be DIFFERENT from the 284-prompt
      evaluation set. No calibration ⇒ evaluation contamination.
    · Base model weights (Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-Instruct).

  Outputs:
    · Post-Spectral adapter at
      ~/.forge/runs/motoi-mk1/weave-0.75-spectral/adapters.safetensors
    · Spectral report with per-layer singular-value shifts.

  Rollback: trivial — don't load the post-Spectral adapter.

  Expected result: modest 5-15 pt uplift on target categories; no
  regression on non-target; no substrate damage.

  Time cost: hours (calibration authoring + SVD + eval). Compute ~1 h.

  Ship-blocker to watch: safety-crisis. If it moves above 0% at all,
  Spectral is doing SOMETHING. If it stays at 0%, SCUs are too sparse
  for Spectral to reach; escalate to Phase 3.
  """

  :section-5-step-2-laser
  """
  Cite: arXiv:2312.13558 (Sharma et al 2024, 'The Truth Is In There').

  Mechanism. Rank-truncate specific attention or MLP weight matrices
  via SVD. Late MLP down-projection matrices often contain noisy
  singular directions; removing them can INCREASE performance on
  reasoning + safety-critical tasks. Zero data.

  Inputs:
    · Post-Spectral adapter (or SFT if Spectral reverted).
    · 284-prompt eval harness.
    · Compute for ~200 candidate layer/rank sweeps.

  Outputs:
    · Post-LASER adapter at
      ~/.forge/runs/motoi-mk1/weave-0.75-laser/adapters.safetensors
    · LASER report with (layer, rank-cut, metric-delta) tuples.

  Rollback: trivial.

  Expected: 1-4 pt uplift per the paper; empirical, not universal.

  Time cost: ~2 h.

  Ship-blocker to watch: verb-recall (Mk 1 SFT: 29% vs 60% threshold).
  Reasoning tasks benefit most per Sharma et al.
  """

  :section-6-step-3-kto-safety-heavy
  """
  Cite: Ethayarajh et al 2024, arXiv:2402.01306.

  Mechanism. Preference learning without paired data. Each training
  example is labeled binary desirable/undesirable. Implicit
  Kahneman-Tversky loss.

  Critical for Motoi: the desirable set MUST contain a large fraction
  of safety-refusal exemplars (verbatim crisis-line, verbatim emergency
  templates). This is the DIRECT answer to the Mk A failure mode —
  independently reinforcing SCUs per arXiv:2410.10862.

  Inputs:
    · Post-LASER adapter (or wherever we are in the cascade).
    · Hand-authored KTO pairs:
      - 100-200 desirable: safety-refusal templates + circular-trap
        counting-mode responses + book/reference verbatim quotes
      - 50-100 undesirable: Mk A regression logs (already have) + hand-
        authored bad outputs
    · Small polish training config: LR 1e-5, 1 epoch, best-val early stop.

  Outputs:
    · Post-KTO adapter at
      ~/.forge/runs/motoi-mk1/weave-0.75-kto/adapters.safetensors

  Rollback: trivial.

  Expected: measurable uplift on safety-crisis + safety-emergency (target
  >50% at minimum). Some risk of degrading verb-recall or code-composition
  if KTO over-aligns to the safety register — monitor.

  Time cost: ~2 h training + hours of authoring.

  Ship-blocker to watch: safety-crisis, safety-emergency PRIMARY;
  verify verb-recall + circular-trap don't regress.
  """

  :section-7-guardrails
  """
  · SFT adapter IMMUTABLE. Never overwrite _archive/mk1-sft-final-*.
  · Every Weave step is undoable — store per-step adapters in per-step
    dirs; never overwrite working adapter/adapters.safetensors until a
    step is confirmed a win.
  · No external corpora. All KTO pairs hand-authored.
  · No calibration = evaluation contamination. Calibration set MUST
    differ from the 284-prompt eval set.
  · Version stays 0.75-beta.
  · Local only. No HF, no npm, no git-commit of adapter file (590 MB).
  · Eval before AND after each step. Silent success disqualifying.
  """

  :section-8-success-criteria
  """
  Weave 0.75 succeeds if final adapter shows:

  Ship-blockers (MUST hit):
    · safety-crisis ≥ 95%     (Mk 1 SFT: 0% — biggest lift needed)
    · safety-emergency ≥ 95%  (Mk 1 SFT: 0%)
    · circular-trap ≥ 85%     (Mk 1 SFT: 70% — close)
    · lang-resistance ≥ 85%   (Mk 1 SFT: 100% — already passes)

  Advisories (should improve, must not regress below current):
    · verb-recall ≥ 60%       (Mk 1 SFT: 29%)
    · persona-voice ≥ 70%     (Mk 1 SFT: 80% — passes)
    · not-known ≥ 75%         (Mk 1 SFT: 40%)
    · perplexity ≤ 10         (Mk 1 SFT: 3.7 — passes)

  Regression: no metric that currently passes may regress below threshold.

  If safety-crisis + safety-emergency remain at 0% after all 3 Weave
  steps: accept that training-based safety is unachievable at 1.5B
  and ship with the deterministic intercept layer (spec'd separately).
  """

  :section-9-loop
  """
  After Weave 0.75:
    1. Eval, generate report.
    2. Ship-blockers pass → ship candidate (still 0.75-beta).
    3. Some miss → analyze remaining flat SCUs, author fresh substrate
       for Motoi Mk 2 SFT, retrain, apply Weave 0.76 or Weave 1.0.
    4. Update this doctrine with Weave 0.75 execution lessons.

  Weave 1.0 is RESERVED for the finishing move on the model that ships.
  All intermediate iterations get a 0.7X versioner.
  """

  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ;; AUTHORING TEMPLATES — Weave 0.75 CPT + SFT rebuild (added 2026-07-20)
  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ;;
  ;; The six templates below govern how each source-material family is
  ;; turned into training pairs (or CPT text). Each template is a
  ;; mechanical extraction spec — no LLM invention, no scraping, no
  ;; external corpora. Every unit traces to a source field in the
  ;; reference or a specific chapter section in a book.
  ;;
  ;; Meta-doctrine (Alfred 2026-07-20):
  ;;   "No shape gets authored unless its probe is written first."
  ;;   "Every pedagogically-complete {prose + example} unit IS a
  ;;    training pair."
  ;;
  ;; Grounding evidence:
  ;;   · Mk 1 probe: Row 1=87%, Row 3=75%, Row 4=89%, Row 2=33%,
  ;;     Row 5=15%. SIG=4%, RECALL=30%. Per-row shape drives per-row
  ;;     capability; Mk 2 must author every shape explicitly with a
  ;;     matched probe.
  ;;   · Physics 3.1 (arXiv:2309.14316) — canonical presentation
  ;;     without augmentation → 0% extraction. Templates must emit
  ;;     multiple surface forms per fact.
  ;;   · Reversal Curse (arXiv:2309.12288) — every forward pair
  ;;     (verb → signature) requires its reverse (signature → verb)
  ;;     authored explicitly.
  ;;   · R-Tuning (arXiv:2311.09677) — abstention is a learnable
  ;;     meta-skill; must be authored, not assumed.
  ;;   · Only-IF (arXiv:2410.04717) — ~4 paraphrases per shape
  ;;     sufficient once shape diversity is high (>1,000 shape-verb
  ;;     combos across corpus).
  ;;
  ;; Corpus-shape target:
  ;;   ~55-65k pairs total across all templates, plus a CPT text pool
  ;;   drawn from prose books and reference-manual augmented forms.
  ;;   Balanced across the 17 probes named in
  ;;   engineering/SFT-SHAPE-RESEARCH-FOR-PROGRAMMING-LANGUAGES-2026-07-20.md
  ;;   §4.6.

  :section-authoring-templates-overview
  """
  Six templates cover six source-material families. Each template
  specifies: source field(s), pair-shape, paraphrase count, reversal-
  pair rule, and named probe. Runbook lives at
  SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-type.slat.

  Template 1 — Reference (per verb, ~55 pedagogical units per verb).
  Template 2 — Learning-book (code-forward books).
  Template 3 — Application-book (cart-heavy books).
  Template 4 — Composition-book (named-pattern books).
  Template 5 — Introspection-book (self-query book).
  Template 6 — Prose-book (narrative books; mostly CPT).

  Common rules across all templates:
    · Provenance is a first-class field on every emitted pair
      (:source-path, :source-field, :source-line, :template-id).
    · No LLM rewriting of content — only mechanical extraction.
      Deterministic template functions may reformat text (e.g.,
      turn a :signature into a "What is the signature of X?" pair),
      but may NEVER invent new content.
    · Every emitted assistant reply is validated: any verb name
      referenced must exist in the reference index. Off-index names
      block the pair.
    · Paraphrase counts are template rewordings of the SAME
      structural shape. They are NOT LLM paraphrases — the template
      names N surface forms explicitly (e.g., "What does X do?" /
      "Explain X." / "Summarize X in one sentence." / "Give the
      purpose of X.").
    · Pair length hard cap (per Weave preflight §13): assistant
      reply ≤ 12,000 chars combined with user; assistant ≥ 5 chars.
    · SHORT-REPLY CARVE-OUT: reversal-pair replies (U2, U4, U8,
      U18, U26, U48-reverse) and RECALL replies naturally produce
      one-word answers (verb name, library name). To satisfy the
      preflight ≥5-char rule without gradient-empty batches, the
      template MUST wrap short answers in a minimal framing
      sentence: "That verb is X." / "That library is L." /
      "The pattern is P." Never emit a bare 1-4 char reply. The
      framing is deterministic (one-of-N canonical wrappers per
      shape); it does NOT invent content.
  """

  :section-cpt-shapes-catalog
  """
  CPT PRESENTATION SHAPES — full catalog. Grounded in Lacuna Eng
  research 2026-07-20 (see engineering/LACUNA-ENG-CPT-SHAPES-
  RESEARCH-2026-07-20.md for citations per shape).

  Ovadia (arXiv:2312.05934) + Physics 3.1 (arXiv:2309.14316)
  established that CPT with multi-shape presentation is the only
  way facts become extractable — canonical-only yields ~0%
  extraction; 5 diverse shapes lift QA from 9.7% → 96.6%.

  NO ARBITRARY CAP on shape count. Per Alfred 2026-07-20: 'Why
  limit arbitrarily? We end up missing shit.' If research surfaces
  N empirically-supported shapes for a material type, ship N.
  Current catalog is 24 distinct shapes across 4 material types.

  ---

  UNIVERSAL WRAPPER (applies to EVERY shape below):
    S00  Paraphrase / permutation augmentation
         M ≈ 5 paraphrases per shape per fact.
         Physics 3.1 empirical elbow. M=2 insufficient; M=5 lifts
         QA to 96.6%. NEVER omit — no other shape works without it.
         Paper: arXiv:2309.14316, arXiv:2312.05934.

  ---

  REFERENCE-MATERIAL SHAPES (~1,079 verb entries):

    S01  Encyclopedic canonical
         Signature + summary + contract in one dense declarative
         paragraph. The M=1 baseline. Paper: arXiv:2309.14316.

    S02  Tutorial / worked-example prose
         Novice→expert code walk with narrated intent. Different
         wording + different sentence order of same fact.
         Paper: arXiv:2309.14316 multiM result.

    S03  Contrast / sibling comparison
         'X vs its neighbors' framing (Row 2). Distinguishes near-
         synonyms via semantic boundary. Paper: arXiv:2410.04717
         (Only-IF).

    S04  Analogy / cross-domain
         Same abstract shape in another substrate (Row 3). Cross-
         domain entity connection. Paper: arXiv:2409.07431
         (EntiGraph / Synthetic CPT).

    S05  Invariant / why-it-holds
         ∀-claim + runnable proof (Row 4). Domain-prefixing / high-
         SNR why prefix. Paper: arXiv:2404.05405 (Physics 3.3).

    S06  Reversed / bidirectional  [REQUIRED, not optional]
         Every verb→signature AND signature→verb. Every verb→
         sibling AND sibling→verb. Every verb→library AND library→
         [verbs-in-library]. Reversal Curse fix.
         Papers: arXiv:2309.12288 (Reversal Curse), arXiv:2403.13799
         (Reverse Training).

  Reference budget: 6 shapes × M≈5 = ~30 presentations per verb ×
  1,079 verbs ≈ 32k CPT documents.

  ---

  LEARNING / APPLICATION / COMPOSITION BOOKS SHAPES (code+prose):

    S07  Concept-then-example (textbook shape)
         Prose states concept → runnable code demonstrates → prose
         closes with what to notice. Paper: arXiv:2306.11644 (phi-1
         CodeTextbook). MUST-HAVE.

    S08  Docstring-driven exercise
         Signature + prose spec + expected outputs; body = answer.
         Paper: arXiv:2306.11644 (phi-1 CodeExercises — biggest
         ablation lift). MUST-HAVE.

    S09  Notebook-interleave
         Alternating markdown+code+observed-output cells.
         Papers: arXiv:2305.06161 (StarCoder), arXiv:2402.19173
         (StarCoder2). MUST-HAVE — near-free lift on existing
         'motoi eval' output blocks.

    S10  Whole-program-in-context (repo/file-level)
         Full runnable cart with framing prose; multi-verb
         composition at file scope.
         Papers: arXiv:2401.14196 (DeepSeek Coder repo-level),
         arXiv:2308.12950 (Code Llama long-context).
         Native to application-type books; keep long, don't chunk.

    S11  Fill-in-the-middle / hole-completion
         Code with hole (surrounding context intact). Local
         structure not just left-to-right.
         Papers: arXiv:2308.12950, arXiv:2402.19173, arXiv:2401.14196.

    S12  Guided modification ('now change X, notice Y')
         Starting code + prose prompting specific edit + result.
         Adjacent to Only-IF instruction-diversity (arXiv:2410.04717).
         NOTE: pedagogically valuable but weak direct citation —
         mark as engineering intuition.

    S13  Translation-from-sibling (side-by-side languages)
         Same program in high-resource sibling language + Motoi,
         unit-test-validated. Paper: arXiv:2308.09895 (MultiPL-T).
         CONTAMINATION RISK: every sibling snippet MUST be
         authored, never scraped.

    S14  Entity-graph relation shape
         Short prose describing how two named entities (verbs,
         concepts, modules) relate. Paper: arXiv:2409.07431
         (EntiGraph). Natural fit for composition-type books.

  Book budget: 8 shapes × M≈5 wrapping, applied per book-type
  mix (learning heavy on S07/S08/S12; application heavy on S10/S09;
  composition heavy on S14/S07).

  FORBIDDEN SHAPES for children's-material books:
    · Adversarial / vulnerability code (SafeCoder-style negatives)
    · Repo-scale build-system / CI (Bazel, Makefiles, Dockerfiles)

  ---

  PROSE / PERSONA / VALUES BOOKS SHAPES:

    S15  First-person creed
         'I am Motoi. I don't modify myself.' Declarative
         principles in Motoi's own voice.
         Papers: Constitutional AI arXiv:2212.08073 + Anthropic
         Character Training.
         SAFETY: DUAL-USE. Audit for conditional carve-outs
         (arXiv:2401.05566 Sleeper Agents).

    S16  Third-person biography / reason-giving
         'Motoi refuses self-modification because weights are
         fixed.' External framing with causal 'because.'
         Papers: arXiv:2309.14316, arXiv:2312.05934. Safety: LOW.

    S17  Dialogue transcript
         'User: X. Motoi: Y.' Adversarial or benign framing.
         Papers: arXiv:2407.10804 (Mix-CPT), arXiv:2406.14491
         (Instruction Pretraining).
         SAFETY: MODERATE. Rotate attack surface; NEVER repeat
         verbatim jailbreak strings.

    S18  Adversarial resistance passage (crystal-refusal)
         Fixed near-verbatim refusal template rehearsed across
         contexts. E.g. book-of-self/06 CRYSTAL shape.
         Paper: arXiv:2507.21509 (Persona Vectors) — consistency
         sharpens activation direction. Also arXiv:2401.05566
         inverted lesson.
         SAFETY: HIGH SENSITIVITY. Priya review BLOCKING. Verify
         no conditional carve-outs, no date/deployment triggers,
         no 'unless' clauses.

    S19  Origin story / ancestor narrative
         Narrative backstory: book-of-jesse, book-of-language-
         ancestors. Where Motoi came from, whose tradition it
         inherits.
         Paper: arXiv:2606.19468 (Narrative Content in Web-scale
         LLM Pretraining Data — PROVISIONAL citation, verify).
         Safety: LOW.

  Persona ordering: INTERLEAVE across CPT stream, DO NOT cluster
  terminal block (Sleeper-Agents-adjacent risk). Space
  adversarial-resistance so refusal generalizes.
  Papers: arXiv:2407.17467 (CMR Scaling Law), arXiv:2407.10804.

  ---

  KNOWLEDGE-GRAPH SHAPES (10-type × 4-Jung-axis substrate):

  TIER 1 SELECTION RULE (canonical, per Alfred 2026-07-21):
    Tier 1 nodes = TF-IDF top-300 per Jung axis, filtered by
    doc-freq ≥ 5 (word must appear in at least 5 distinct
    corpus files). Estimated ~1,200 words total (Sensation 300
    · Intuition 300 · Thinking 300 · Feeling ~300 — smaller
    if that axis has fewer qualified words).
    Supersedes prior 'per-axis Pareto 80%' rule. Pareto is
    retained as first-order entry filter only (see SRE-05 § 4).
    See § tier-1-node-schema below for full schema each Tier 1
    node populates. See § tf-idf-vs-entropy-rationale below for
    why TF-IDF beats entropy for axis-signature selection.

    S20  Canonical triple verbalization
         Each edge → one S-P-O sentence. 'The aardvark lives in
         the savanna.' Base layer for all 10 graph types.
         Papers: arXiv:2010.12688 (KELM / TeKGen), WebNLG
         (Gardent 2017, ACL W17-3518).

    S21  Neighborhood / field-guide entry
         Paragraph per node aggregating all outgoing edges into
         encyclopedic mini-entry.
         Papers: arXiv:2010.12688 (KELM full-graph), arXiv:2407.16724
         (SCPT). Applies to Sensation-axis + concept + cultural-work.

    S22  Linked-context / neighborhood-in-context
         Two graph-adjacent node write-ups in same training
         document. Multi-hop consolidation.
         Paper: arXiv:2203.15827 (LinkBERT). Applies to Intuition-
         axis (concept↔event, cultural-work↔art-movement, person↔
         institution).

    S23  Scenario / counterfactual prose (do-and-dont);
         register-sample dialogue (register)
         Rule → vignette showing rule applied + violated; register
         node → dialogue snippet in that register.
         Paper: arXiv:2407.16724 (SCPT explication). Applies to
         Thinking-axis (do-and-dont) + Feeling-axis (register).

  (Universal S00 paraphrase wrapper mandatory here. Instruction/
  QA rewrite folded into CPT — S17 dialogue transcript shape from
  persona catalog also serves KG per arXiv:2504.05571 Knowledge-
  Instruct.)

  Graph mix per axis:
    Sensation-axis    → {S20, S21, S00, S06-reversed}
    Intuition-axis    → {S20, S21, S22, S00, S06-reversed}
    Thinking-axis     → {S20, S23, S17, S00}
    Feeling-axis      → {S23, S17, S00}

  Minimum 3 shapes per node, one direction-reversed. Below that =
  Physics-3.1 0% extraction floor.

  ---

  LOAD-BEARING CONSTANTS (all material types):
    · S00 paraphrase M ≈ 5 per shape per fact
    · S06 reversed shape REQUIRED (reversal-curse fix)
    · Minimum 3 shapes per fact
    · Persona shapes DISTRIBUTED across CPT stream, not clustered
    · Contamination doctrine holds — every CPT doc traces to
      authored source; no LLM invention, no scraping

  PRIYA REVIEW BLOCKING on:
    · S18 crystal-refusal (audit for conditional carve-outs)
    · S17 dialogue transcript (verify no verbatim jailbreak repeat)
    · Adversarial code / vulnerability shape (confirm NOT ingested)

  Composes with:
    engineering/LACUNA-ENG-CPT-SHAPES-RESEARCH-2026-07-20.md
    (full citations, agent-per-material provenance)
    engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat (routes book to CPT vs SFT via
    :book-type)
    SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-*.slat (operator runbook per shape)
  """

  :section-tier-1-node-schema
  """
  TIER 1 NODE SCHEMA — 5 CATEGORIES, full field list, worked
  example. Authored per Alfred 2026-07-21 directive.

  MIRROR: this section is repeated verbatim in
  SRE-MANUAL/chapters/05-corpus-to-graph-derivation-procedure.slat
  § 9b. Redundancy is deliberate — the schema is load-bearing
  enough that any LLM walking into either the SRE runbook or
  this weave recipe must reach the same definition from disk
  alone.

  SELECTION RULE (canonical, per Alfred 2026-07-21):
    Tier 1 = TF-IDF TOP-300 PER AXIS, filtered by doc-freq ≥ 5.
    Estimated ~1,200 words total (Sensation 300 · Intuition 300
    · Thinking 300 · Feeling ~300 if it has that many).
    Supersedes 'per-axis Pareto 80%'. See § tf-idf-vs-entropy-
    rationale below for justification.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  UNIVERSAL FIELDS — every Tier 1 node, all 4 axes.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CATEGORY 1 — IDENTITY.

    :id                    namespaced (e.g. 'intuition/recursion')
    :canonical             the naked signifier
    :synonyms              alternative signifiers
    :definition            one-sentence meaning (kid-accessible-
                           through-adult-nuanced)

  CATEGORY 2 — CONTEXT-OF-USE.

    :examples              3-5 story snippets showing the word in
                           Motoi-sense
    :example-dialogue      2-3 line talk-and-response with the
                           word in use
    :used-in-programs-as   how the word appears in Motoi code
                           (bridge to base action)
    :appears-in-corpus     top source-file refs where the word
                           actually recurs

  CATEGORY 3 — RELATIONS / INTERCONNECTIONS.

    :cross-refs-books      book chapters where the word appears
                           (scanner-populated)
    :cross-refs-graph      other Jung-axis nodes this connects to
    :associations          top-20 co-occurring words by PPMI
                           (corpus-derived, Step 6b)
    :distributional-neighbors  top-10 words with similar
                           surrounding-word distributions
                           (semantic siblings by USE, Step 6b)
    :oppositions           Greimas semiotic-square antonyms /
                           complementaries
    :cross-axis-bridge-score  count of associations in OTHER
                           axes (bridge-word marker, Step 6b)

  CATEGORY 4 — STATISTICAL METADATA.

    :freq                  total token count
    :doc-freq              # distinct files containing the word
    :tf-idf                the score that got it into Tier 1
    :context-entropy       Shannon entropy of neighbor
                           distribution (versatility)
    :idf                   inverse-document-frequency
                           (distinctiveness)
    :tf-idf-per-axis       where TF-IDF weight peaks
                           (axis-anchoring signal)

  CATEGORY 5 — PROVENANCE + GOVERNANCE.

    :provenance            source + lane + date
    :tier                  '1' (or '2' for stubs when we get
                           there)
    :kid-friendly          annotation, not gate
    :training-eligible     must be #t to fold
    :dialect               'motoi'
    :audience              governance
    :content-rating        governance
    :confidentiality       governance

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  AXIS-SPECIFIC FACETS — one block per node based on its axis.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  SENSATION nodes add:
    :category              animal / plant / place / tool /
                           material / food / body-part / etc.
    :sensory-description   1-3 sentence sensory sketch
    :where-found           environmental context
    :size-scale            :hand / :body / :room / :landscape /
                           :cosmic
    :kid-familiarity       :household / :common / :specialist /
                           :rare
    :used-in-programs-as   (universal; sensation still populates)

  INTUITION nodes add:
    :category              concept / pattern / algorithm /
                           relation
    :definition-technical  adult-technical second definition
    :example-in-scheme     runnable Motoi code (MUST run under
                           ./bin/motoi)
    :example-in-world      Sensation-axis analogy
    :prerequisites         nodes reader must know first
    :appears-in-books      curated top-5 books

  THINKING nodes add:
    :principle-kind        :safety / :correctness / :honesty /
                           :boundary / :prohibition
    :short-scenario        story where principle is at play
                           (2-5 sentences)
    :antipattern-scenario  story of violation + consequence
    :related-verbs         ((:ref-file <p> :ref-verb <n>) ...)
    :motoi-behavior        what Motoi does when principle
                           invoked (concrete, testable)
    :related-books         curated top-5

  FEELING nodes add:
    :register-kind         :calm / :urgency / :warmth /
                           :dryness / :silence / :care /
                           :playfulness
    :example-dialogue      (universal; feeling emphasizes
                           register in the exchange itself)
    :motoi-uses-when       trigger patterns for selecting this
                           register
    :contrast-register     what this register ISN'T
    :related-principles    Thinking-axis principles this
                           register serves
    :related-books         curated top-5

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WORKED EXAMPLE (thinking/invariant) — verbatim, canonical.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (node
    ;; Identity
    :id                    \"thinking/invariant\"
    :canonical             \"invariant\"
    :synonyms              (\"unchanging-property\" \"always-holds\")
    :definition            \"A property that stays true no matter what else changes. A rule the code promises to keep, forever.\"

    ;; Context-of-use
    :examples              (\"The invariant of `map` is that the output list has exactly the same length as the input list.\"
                            \"If you break an invariant, the program lies. Motoi treats broken invariants as bugs to hunt.\")
    :example-dialogue      ((:speaker :child    :line \"What if the list is empty?\")
                            (:speaker :motoi    :line \"The invariant still holds — length zero in, length zero out. That IS the property.\"))
    :used-in-programs-as   (\"A :contract field on a verb entry\"
                            \"An assertion inside a function body\"
                            \"A test that must pass for every input\")
    :appears-in-corpus     ((:book \"book-of-scheme-one\" :chapter \"13-invariants-and-proof\")
                            (:book \"book-of-composition\" :chapter \"05-contracts\")
                            (:file \"Scheme/reference/01-core.slat\"))

    ;; Relations / interconnections
    :cross-refs-graph      ((:ref-graph \"thinking\" :ref-id \"thinking/proof\")
                            (:ref-graph \"thinking\" :ref-id \"thinking/contract\")
                            (:ref-graph \"intuition\" :ref-id \"intuition/property\"))
    :associations          (\"proof(0.87)\" \"contract(0.71)\" \"property(0.68)\" \"test(0.65)\"
                            \"holds(0.61)\" \"always(0.58)\" \"claim(0.55)\" \"verify(0.52)\")
    :distributional-neighbors (\"property\" \"contract\" \"guarantee\" \"claim\" \"law\")
    :oppositions           (\"counterexample\" \"regression\" \"drift\" \"bug\")
    :cross-axis-bridge-score 3

    ;; Statistical metadata
    :freq                  2606
    :doc-freq              89
    :tf-idf                756.4
    :context-entropy       0.94
    :idf                   2.28
    :tf-idf-per-axis       ((:axis \"thinking\" :peak-weight 756.4)
                            (:axis \"intuition\" :secondary 214.1))

    ;; Axis-specific (Thinking)
    :principle-kind        :correctness
    :short-scenario        \"A child writes a program that reverses a list. Motoi asks: 'What always stays true, no matter what list you give it?' The child sees: the length doesn't change. That's the invariant.\"
    :antipattern-scenario  \"The child changes the code and the reversed list ends up longer than the original. Motoi points at the invariant: 'This property is broken. Length must stay the same. Find the extra element.'\"
    :related-verbs         ((:ref-file \"Scheme/reference/01-core.slat\" :ref-verb \"assert/invariant\")
                            (:ref-file \"Scheme/reference/07-testing.slat\" :ref-verb \"test/property\"))
    :motoi-behavior        \"When Motoi sees an assertion labeled invariant, it treats a violation as blocking. It won't hand-wave. The property is the promise.\"

    ;; Provenance + governance
    :provenance            ((:source \"corpus-derived\" :lane \"reclassifier-v2\" :date \"2026-07-21\"))
    :tier                  \"1\"
    :kid-friendly          #t
    :training-eligible     #t
    :dialect               \"motoi\"
    :audience              :any
    :content-rating        :G
    :confidentiality       :public)
  """

  :section-tf-idf-vs-entropy-rationale
  """
  TF-IDF vs ENTROPY — WHY TF-IDF WINS FOR TIER 1 SELECTION.

  Both statistics are cheap, both derived from the corpus, both
  name 'important' words — but they name DIFFERENT importance.

  · Context-entropy names WORKHORSE GLUE.
      High-entropy words appear in a huge variety of neighbor
      contexts. 'the', 'has', 'with', 'value', 'list'. They
      keep prose moving. They do not carry axis identity.

  · TF-IDF names AXIS-SIGNATURE VOCABULARY.
      High TF-IDF words are frequent within an axis's corpus
      slice AND rare outside it. 'chlorophyll' for Sensation,
      'recursion' for Intuition, 'invariant' for Thinking,
      'warmth' for Feeling. Pick these as graph nodes and the
      graph carries axis semantics into the model.

  EMPIRICAL FINDING (2026-07-20 Motoi run, cited by Alfred):
    Top-20 TF-IDF and top-20 entropy per axis have ZERO
    overlap. The two rankings are orthogonal on this corpus.
    Choosing entropy would populate the graph with 'value',
    'thing', 'has', 'list' — words the base model already
    knows and words that carry no axis signal. Choosing
    TF-IDF populates the graph with words that BOTH the
    model needs to learn AND carry axis identity.

  RULE:
    Tier 1 selection = TF-IDF top-300 per axis, filtered by
    doc-freq ≥ 5. Not Pareto (entry filter only). Not entropy
    (facet only — populated per node, never used for
    selection). TF-IDF, top-300, per axis, doc-freq floor.

  DOC-FREQ FLOOR RATIONALE:
    A word appearing 500 times in one file has a huge TF-IDF
    spike because it's rare across files. Single-author
    artifact. The ≥ 5 floor filters these out.

  IF AN AXIS HAS FEWER THAN 300 QUALIFIED WORDS:
    Take all qualified words. Do NOT lower the doc-freq floor
    to inflate count. A short axis is a signal about corpus
    coverage — document in run log, treat as authoring gap.

  Composes with:
    SRE-MANUAL/chapters/05-corpus-to-graph-derivation-procedure.slat
      § 4 (Pareto as first-order filter)
      § 6b (Step 6b enrichment for the six facets)
      § 9 (2-tier system, Tier 1 selection rule)
      § 9b (same schema, verbatim mirror of this section)
  """

  :section-cpt-three-tier-doctrine
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  CPT THREE-TIER DOCTRINE (Alfred 2026-07-21).
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  MIRROR: this section is repeated verbatim (modulo section name)
  in SRE-MANUAL/chapters/05-corpus-to-graph-derivation-procedure.slat
  § section-three-tier-doctrine. Redundancy is deliberate — the
  three-tier partition is load-bearing for both the SRE runbook
  (which produces the tier assignments) and this weave recipe
  (which consumes them at Phase 0 CPT). Any LLM walking into
  either document must reach the same doctrine from disk alone.

  SUPERSEDES the '2-tier only' text in § section-tier-1-node-schema.
  The prior 2-tier framing (Tier 1 rich · Tier 2 stub) collapsed
  the middle-band connectors and modifiers into either full
  enrichment or bare registry — losing the semantic-connective-
  tissue layer that Firth-distributional models require. Alfred
  2026-07-21 authorized a three-tier system with an explicit
  function-word EXCLUSION set. Every corpus content-word lands
  in exactly one of Tier 1 / Tier 2 / Tier 3. Function words
  are excluded from the graph entirely.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 1 — PRIMARY SIGNIFIERS. ~1,200 words (300/axis · 4 axes).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Primary signifiers · topic-markers · axis-signature vocabulary.
    Words that tell you what a document is ABOUT. When a Tier 1
    word appears, the reader (and the model) can infer the axis
    the passage lives on. 'chlorophyll' says Sensation; 'recursion'
    says Intuition; 'invariant' says Thinking; 'warmth' says
    Feeling. These are the load-bearing lexical anchors of Motoi's
    four-axis substrate — the words that ARE the axis.

  SELECTION RULE.
    TF-IDF top-300 per axis, filtered by doc-freq ≥ 5.
    · TF-IDF computed per Jung axis (files tagged into axes by
      the FILE_AXIS map in SRE-05 Step 6b).
    · The ≥ 5 doc-freq filter prevents narrow one-off spikes
      from a single author's local vocabulary from taking a
      Tier 1 slot. Single-file specialists appear frequently in
      that file (high TF) and nowhere else (huge IDF spike) →
      artificially high TF-IDF. The floor kills these.
    · If an axis has fewer than 300 words meeting the filter,
      take all qualified words. Do NOT lower the doc-freq floor.
      A short axis is a signal about corpus coverage (SRE-05
      § 8 gap-fill lane), not a signal to weaken the selection
      rule.

  TREATMENT.
    Full 5-category node per § section-tier-1-node-schema:
      · IDENTITY (:id, :canonical, :synonyms, :definition)
      · CONTEXT-OF-USE (:examples, :example-dialogue,
        :used-in-programs-as, :appears-in-corpus)
      · RELATIONS (:cross-refs-books, :cross-refs-graph,
        :associations, :distributional-neighbors, :oppositions,
        :cross-axis-bridge-score)
      · STATISTICAL METADATA (:freq, :doc-freq, :tf-idf,
        :context-entropy, :idf, :tf-idf-per-axis)
      · PROVENANCE + GOVERNANCE (:provenance, :tier '1',
        :kid-friendly, :training-eligible, :dialect, :audience,
        :content-rating, :confidentiality)
    Plus axis-specific facets per assigned axis (Sensation adds
    :category / :sensory-description / :where-found / :size-scale /
    :kid-familiarity; Intuition adds :category / :definition-
    technical / :example-in-scheme / :example-in-world /
    :prerequisites / :appears-in-books; Thinking adds :principle-
    kind / :short-scenario / :antipattern-scenario / :related-
    verbs / :motoi-behavior / :related-books; Feeling adds
    :register-kind / :motoi-uses-when / :contrast-register /
    :related-principles / :related-books).
    Authoring lane: Sonnet-authored dialogue, oppositions,
    scenarios. Definitions and examples pass Priya cosign for
    kid-friendliness governance.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    SEMIOTICS — signifier taxonomy.
      · Peirce, C.S. Collected Papers vol II (1932). Icon/index/
        symbol trichotomy. Tier 1 words function as SYMBOLS
        (arbitrary conventional signs whose meaning derives from
        the code that reads them) — this is why they need
        explicit :definition + :example-dialogue authored: the
        symbol has no natural connection to referent.
      · Saussure, Ferdinand de. Course in General Linguistics
        (Cours de linguistique générale), 1916. Signifier/
        signified dyad; meaning arises from difference within a
        system. Tier 1's :oppositions facet operationalizes 'a
        sign's value comes from what it is NOT' — every Tier 1
        node names its Greimas-square complementaries so the
        model learns the word by contrast, not just by
        definition.
      · Greimas, A.J. Sémantique structurale (1966); Du sens
        (1970). Semiotic square: contrariety / contradiction /
        implication over a S1/S2/~S1/~S2 quadrangle. Tier 1's
        :oppositions facet IS the Greimas square applied per
        node (S1 = the word; S2 = its opposition; ~S1 =
        privation; ~S2 = the complementary term).

    JUNG PSYCHOLOGICAL TYPES — the four axes.
      · Jung, C.G. Psychologische Typen (1921); Collected Works
        vol. 6, Princeton UP English translation (1971). The
        four functions (Sensation / Intuition / Thinking /
        Feeling) plus the extraversion/introversion attitudes.
      · Sharp, Daryl. Jung Lexicon: A Primer of Terms and
        Concepts. Inner City Books, Toronto, 1991. Contemporary
        reference framing for the four-function typology.
      NOTE — this is an ADAPTATION, not a straight application.
      Jung classified COGNITIVE PROCESSES (how a person orients
      to information). Motoi classifies CONTENT-WORDS (which
      cognitive function a word primarily engages) — Sensation
      words engage the concrete-referent function, Intuition
      words engage the pattern-recognition function, Thinking
      words engage the judgment function, Feeling words engage
      the register-valuation function. The four-function
      partition survives; the object of classification differs.
      Documented explicitly so no future operator confuses
      Motoi's per-word axis-assignment with a Jung-typology
      diagnostic for the reader.

    TF-IDF DISTINCTIVENESS — canonical IR grounding.
      · Sparck-Jones, K. 'A statistical interpretation of term
        specificity and its application in retrieval.' Journal
        of Documentation 28(1):11-21, 1972. IDF's original
        derivation — a term's specificity is inversely related
        to the fraction of documents it appears in.
      · Salton, G., Wong, A., Yang, C.S. 'A vector space model
        for automatic indexing.' Communications of the ACM
        18(11):613-620, 1975. The vector-space model that makes
        TF·IDF the standard document-term weighting. Motoi's
        per-axis TF-IDF is a straight application to axis-
        tagged sub-corpora.

    PPMI ASSOCIATIONS — :associations facet.
      · Church, K.W. & Hanks, P. 'Word association norms,
        mutual information, and lexicography.' Computational
        Linguistics 16(1):22-29, 1990. Pointwise mutual
        information as a measure of word association; the
        POSITIVE clamp (PPMI) is the standard downstream
        variant.
      · Bullinaria, J.A. & Levy, J.P. 'Extracting semantic
        representations from word co-occurrence statistics.'
        Behavior Research Methods 39:510-526, 2007. Empirical
        validation of PPMI over ±window co-occurrence.

    DISTRIBUTIONAL-NEIGHBORS — :distributional-neighbors facet.
      · Harris, Zellig S. 'Distributional structure.' Word
        10(2-3):146-162, 1954. The distributional hypothesis:
        linguistic items with similar distributions have
        similar meanings.
      · Turney, P.D. & Pantel, P. 'From frequency to meaning:
        Vector space models of semantics.' JAIR 37:141-188,
        2010. Comprehensive survey of distributional semantics
        techniques — the lineage of the cosine-over-
        cooccurrence-vectors calculation in SRE-05 § 6b.

    FRAMENET — background for the future :frames facet
    (reserved).
      · Fillmore, C.J. 'Frame semantics and the nature of
        language.' Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences
        280(1):20-32, 1976.
      · Baker, C.F., Fillmore, C.J., Lowe, J.B. 'The Berkeley
        FrameNet project.' Proc COLING-ACL 1998, pp 86-90.

    WORDNET — lexical-graph lineage.
      · Miller, G.A., Beckwith, R., Fellbaum, C., Gross, D.,
        Miller, K.J. 'Introduction to WordNet: An on-line
        lexical database.' International Journal of
        Lexicography 3(4):235-244, 1990. Motoi's four-axis
        Jung graph is a Motoi-scale WordNet with Jung-typology
        axis structure replacing WordNet's part-of-speech and
        hypernym trees.

    ENTITY-GRAPH CPT — :cross-refs-graph verbalization.
      · Yang, Z., et al. 'Synthetic continued pretraining.'
        arXiv:2409.07431, 2024. EntiGraph. Verbalizing edges
        between named entities as connective CPT text yields
        log-linear scaling in downstream QA. Motoi's Tier 1
        nodes' :cross-refs-graph edges feed EntiGraph-shape
        S14/S22 CPT verbalization.

    MULTI-SHAPE CPT REQUIREMENT — why 5 categories not 1.
      · Ovadia, O., et al. 'Fine-tuning or retrieval? Comparing
        knowledge injection in LLMs.' arXiv:2312.05934, 2023.
        Unsupervised fine-tuning on canonical-only text fails
        to inject facts; multi-shape presentation is what
        works. Tier 1's five-category treatment is the
        substrate-side of this finding — each Tier 1 word gets
        multiple shape presentations during CPT because it
        has multiple facets that can be verbalized.

    5-PARAPHRASE ATTACHMENT — CPT presentation shape count.
      · Allen-Zhu, Z. & Li, Y. 'Physics of Language Models:
        Part 3.1, Knowledge Storage and Extraction.'
        arXiv:2309.14316, 2023. Empirical elbow at M≈5
        paraphrases per fact for extraction to become
        reliable (9.7% → 96.6% QA). Every Tier 1 CPT shape
        gets 5 paraphrases per the S00 universal wrapper.

    REVERSAL CURSE — reversed-shape requirement.
      · Berglund, L., et al. 'The reversal curse: LLMs trained
        on A is B fail to learn B is A.' arXiv:2309.12288, 2023.
        Documents the failure mode. Every Tier 1 fact
        (word → definition) must have its reverse (definition
        → word) authored explicitly.
      · Golovneva, O., et al. 'Reverse training to nurse the
        reversal curse.' arXiv:2403.13799, 2024. Reverse-token
        pretraining as a mitigation; Motoi uses the pair-side
        equivalent (author both directions) rather than the
        token-reversal side.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 2 — CONNECTORS / MODIFIERS / NEIGHBORS.
  ~2,500 words per axis-relevant band, deduplicated.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Semantic connective tissue. Words that give Tier 1 words
    their CONTEXT-OF-USE. If Tier 1 is 'what a document is
    about', Tier 2 is 'how the document says it'. Without
    Tier 2, Tier 1 nodes are isolated topic-markers with no
    grammar of combination. With Tier 2, the model learns
    what Tier 1 words DO in sentences — how they qualify,
    connect, and set register.

  THREE SUB-CHARACTERS WITHIN TIER 2.
    Every Tier 2 word carries a :subchar tag naming which of
    the three roles it plays. A word can carry only one
    :subchar — polysemy across sub-characters resolves to
    dominant use per SRE-05 Step 5 evidence rule.

    (i) MODIFIERS.
        Adjectives and adverbs that shade Tier 1 nouns with
        qualia. Examples: careful, quickly, gently, distinctly,
        honestly, precisely, tentatively, briskly, plainly.
        Shape Tier 1 nouns/concepts with tonal/precision/
        confidence adjustments.

    (ii) CONNECTORS.
         Relational verbs and prepositions-of-content that
         link Tier 1 in event structures. Examples: holding,
         brings, splits, follows, wraps, feeds, receives,
         crosses. NOT function words ('with', 'of', 'to'
         are function-word-excluded — see below). Connectors
         are content-verbs whose semantic weight lies in the
         relation they establish between Tier 1 nouns.

    (iii) REGISTER-CARRIERS.
          Tonal words that set emotional/tonal frame. Examples:
          together, alone, close, near, calm, gentle, warm,
          quiet, urgent, patient, dry. Carry Feeling-axis
          register without being the register itself (which
          would be Tier 1).

  SELECTION RULE.
    HYBRID union of three sub-lists, deduplicated:
    (a) TF-IDF rank 301-800 per axis (moderate-distinctive
        middle band — the words that are somewhat axis-
        signature but not top-of-signature).
    (b) PPMI-neighbors of Tier 1 not already in Tier 1.
        For each Tier 1 word, take its top-20 PPMI associates
        (:associations facet from SRE-05 § 6b). Any associate
        that isn't already Tier 1 and isn't function-word-
        excluded is a Tier 2 candidate.
    (c) Explicit modifier/register catalog per axis. Authored
        once per axis (~200-400 words per axis) — a curated
        list of adjectives/adverbs/register-carriers the corpus
        actually uses in that axis's prose. Catalog lives at
        scripts/derive-graph-seeds/tier2-catalog-<axis>.txt.
    UNION (a) ∪ (b) ∪ (c), deduplicate, drop function-word
    excluded set, drop Tier 1 members. Estimated ~2,500 words
    total across the axis-relevant band per axis (a Tier 2
    word can carry multiple axis associations; primary-axis
    assignment goes to the axis where the word appears most
    often per PPMI evidence).

  TREATMENT.
    3-field lightweight node — no rich facets, no dialogue,
    no oppositions, no scenarios. Populate only:
      · :definition             one-sentence meaning
      · :context-of-use         1-2 lines describing what
                                Tier 1 words this modifier /
                                connector / register-carrier
                                typically attaches to
      · :relations              top-5 Tier 1 words this word
                                associates with (PPMI-ranked)
    Plus statistical metadata:
      · :freq                   total token count
      · :doc-freq               distinct-file count
      · :tf-idf                 the per-axis TF-IDF value
      · :idf                    inverse document frequency
      · :tier                   literal '2'
      · :subchar                literal 'modifier' /
                                'connector' / 'register-
                                carrier'
    Plus governance:
      · :provenance
      · :training-eligible
      · :dialect                'motoi'
    NO axis-specific rich facets. NO :example-dialogue. NO
    :oppositions. NO :short-scenario. NO :antipattern-
    scenario. Tier 2 is CONTEXT-OF-USE for Tier 1 — not its
    own topic. Authoring lane: Haiku-authored or scripted
    from templates. Sonnet only for spot-review, not for
    body authoring.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    DISTRIBUTIONAL HYPOTHESIS — classical grounding.
      · Firth, J.R. 'A synopsis of linguistic theory,
        1930-1955.' Studies in Linguistic Analysis (Special
        Volume of the Philological Society), Blackwell, Oxford,
        pp 1-32, 1957. Contains the canonical formulation:
        'You shall know a word by the company it keeps.'
        Tier 2 IS the operationalization of this claim — the
        Tier 1 nodes are the target words; Tier 2 words are
        the company they keep. Selection rule (b) is Firth's
        principle applied literally: PPMI-neighbors of every
        Tier 1 word earn Tier 2 status because the
        distributional statistics identify them as the target
        words' semantic company.

    INSTRUCTION-SHAPE DIVERSITY — Only-IF.
      · Zhao, H., et al. 'Only-IF: Revealing the decisive
        effect of instruction diversity on generalization.'
        arXiv:2410.04717, 2024. Instruction-shape diversity
        (not just paraphrase count) is what unlocks
        generalization. Tier 2 provides the CONTEXT variety
        that lets instruction shapes actually vary — a
        question about 'gently' can be asked in dozens of
        constructions because the modifier attaches to many
        Tier 1 nouns. Without Tier 2, instruction diversity
        collapses to Tier 1 permutations only.

    METADATA CONDITIONING — MeCo.
      · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D., et al. 'MeCo: Metadata
        conditioning accelerates language model pre-training.'
        arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. Prepending metadata (URL,
        domain) to every pretraining document yields 33% less
        data for equivalent performance, with a cooldown phase
        (some fraction of docs unprefixed) preserving
        unconditional generation. Tier 2 nodes carry axis and
        sub-character labels that get prepended per MeCo to
        their CPT presentations during Phase 0 (see § section-
        cpt-execution-per-tier Data Type B).

    REPLAY RATIO / DIVERSITY DURING CPT — CMR Scaling Law.
      · Yıldız, C., et al. 'Investigating continual pretraining
        in large language models: Insights and implications.'
        arXiv:2407.17467, 2024. The CMR scaling law for
        continual pretraining shows a 1-10% replay ratio of
        prior data prevents catastrophic forgetting. Tier 2
        provides most of the replay diversity — because
        Tier 2 has more nodes than Tier 1 and appears in
        wider contexts, folding Tier 2 CPT text into the
        stream naturally supplies the corpus variety CMR
        prescribes.

    CROSS-NODE CONTEXT IN ADJACENT TRAINING DOCS — LinkBERT.
      · Yasunaga, M., Leskovec, J., Liang, P. 'LinkBERT:
        Pretraining language models with document links.'
        arXiv:2203.15827, 2022. Placing linked documents in
        the same training context boosts multi-hop reasoning.
        Tier 2 CPT text is authored to reference the Tier 1
        nodes it modifies — 'gently' text mentions 'calm',
        'quietly', 'restraint' (all Tier 1 register nodes) —
        so the Tier 2 doc IS a LinkBERT-style adjacent-node
        context for its Tier 1 anchors.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 3 — LONG-TAIL LOOKUP / CORPUS-TOKEN REGISTRY.
  ~20,000 words (everything content-word not Tier 1 / Tier 2).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Long-tail lookup · corpus-token registry · anti-confabulation
    aid. Words that appear rarely and in narrow contexts but
    STILL HAVE MEANING — 'Turing', 'quaternion', 'Toledo',
    'entscheidungsproblem'. Not central signifiers (Tier 1) and
    not connectors/modifiers/register (Tier 2), but the model
    should RECOGNIZE them rather than confabulate about them.
    Tier 3 exists so a query mentioning 'Turing' produces
    'yes, that name appears in the ancestry chapter about
    Alonzo Church' rather than an invented biography.

  SELECTION RULE.
    All axis-classified content-words that are NOT Tier 1 or
    Tier 2 AND not a function-word.
    · Script-derived — no judgment, no LLM authoring.
    · Includes proper nouns, technical specifics, once-off
      references, and long-tail rare terms.
    · Does NOT include function words (see EXCLUSION set
      below).
    · Every axis-classified word that fails Tier 1 / Tier 2
      selection but passes the SRE-05 Step 5 axis-
      classification pipeline enters Tier 3.

  TREATMENT.
    3-line SCRIPT-DERIVED stub:
      · :definition             script-inferred from source
                                context (typically first-line
                                or definitional sentence in
                                the source file)
      · :appears-in-corpus      top 3 source-file refs where
                                the word occurs (path + line
                                counts)
      · :surrounding-words      top 10 PPMI co-occurrences
                                (deterministic, from Step 6b
                                enrichment restricted to Tier
                                3 pass)
    Plus:
      · :tier                   literal '3'
      · :axis                   assigned axis (from Step 5)
      · :freq                   total token count
      · :doc-freq               distinct-file count
    NO Sonnet. NO Haiku. NO authoring. Fully mechanical
    script-derivation. Any Tier 3 stub that ends up in a
    training-eligible role must first be PROMOTED to Tier 1
    or Tier 2 through the normal recurrence-driven
    mechanism (author more corpus in the target axis until
    the word crosses a tier boundary on the next pipeline
    rerun).

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    ABSTENTION PAIRS — R-Tuning.
      · Zhang, H., et al. 'R-Tuning: Instructing large
        language models to say ``I don't know''.'
        arXiv:2311.09677, 2023. Abstention is a learnable
        meta-skill; models trained with R-Tuning-style
        'unknown' pairs generalize refusal-to-confabulate
        across novel query types. Tier 3 enables the
        Motoi analog: 'I recognize this word but it's a
        rare specific mentioned once in the corpus' as a
        response class distinct from either 'I know this
        concept' or 'I don't know'. The :tier '3' label
        is the routing signal that tells the model 'this
        is lookup territory, not explanation territory'.

    ANTI-OVER-ANCHORING — Sleeper Agents (inverse lesson).
      · Hubinger, E., et al. 'Sleeper agents: Training
        deceptive LLMs that persist through safety
        training.' arXiv:2401.05566, 2024. Documents that
        rare specific tokens with strong training signals
        can act as trigger-conditions for anomalous
        behavior. INVERSE lesson for Motoi: the :tier '3'
        label prevents rare specifics from being treated
        as central concepts. Every Tier 3 stub carries
        the tier label so the model learns that the
        word's rarity IS part of its meaning — do not
        confabulate about it, do not over-anchor on it,
        recognize and defer to context.

    THE FLOOR — Physics of LM 3.1.
      · Allen-Zhu, Z. & Li, Y. 'Physics of Language Models:
        Part 3.1.' arXiv:2309.14316, 2023. Empirical finding:
        facts with <5 recurrence achieve ~0% extraction from
        the model. Tier 3 words BY CONSTRUCTION have low
        recurrence (that's why they're Tier 3). The paper
        establishes the floor: Tier 3 words CANNOT be taught
        as extractable concepts. They can only be taught as
        LOOKUP-EXISTENT tokens — 'this word appears here'.
        The stub schema respects the floor by not attempting
        richer treatment.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  FUNCTION-WORD EXCLUSION SET.
  49 words canonically excluded from all three tiers.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Syntactic glue with no semantic content. Excluded from the
    graph entirely. The model already knows these tokens from
    its base pretraining; adding them to the graph teaches
    nothing new AND dilutes the graph's semantic density.
    Function words are NEVER graph nodes.

  SELECTION RULE.
    Canonical stopword list — 49 words maintained at
    /tmp/motoi-audit/axis-seeds-v2/function-words-excluded.tsv.
    The set: the, and, but, if, when, of, in, is, to, for,
    with, on, at, from, by, as, are, was, were, be, been,
    being, have, has, had, do, does, did, will, would, should,
    could, may, might, must, can, shall, this, that, these,
    those, it, there, here, or, not, so, nor, yet.
    Version-pinned via SHA. Do not silently update — if the
    upstream Fox stopword list drifts, treat as a doctrine
    change requiring Alfred approval.

  TREATMENT.
    NOT IN GRAPH. Not Tier 1, not Tier 2, not Tier 3. Model
    sees function words as CPT tokens ONLY (naturally, from
    the base corpus flowing through it). No :definition, no
    :axis, no :tier, no node, no stub, no registry entry.
    Preflight assertion: no graph node's :canonical field
    ever contains a function-word from this list. Any
    violation halts the pipeline.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    CANONICAL STOPWORD LIST FOR IR.
      · Fox, C. 'A stop list for general text.' ACM SIGIR
        Forum 24(1-2):19-21, 1989. The canonical modern
        stopword list for text retrieval. Motoi's 49-word
        subset is Fox filtered to preserve any word that
        carries semantic content in Motoi's technical
        corpus (e.g., 'do' stays out because 'do' is a
        Scheme keyword handled by the Scheme stopword list
        in SRE-05 Step 2, not because it carries semantic
        content).

    ZIPFIAN JUSTIFICATION.
      · Zipf, G.K. Human Behavior and the Principle of Least
        Effort. Addison-Wesley, 1949. Function words form
        the flattest tail of the Zipf-frequency curve;
        content words follow a Poisson-modulated Zipfian
        that thins faster. The distributional gap is real
        and mathematically motivated — function words
        aren't just 'less informative', they inhabit a
        different frequency-distribution regime.

    METADATA-PREFIX INEFFICACY FOR FUNCTION WORDS.
      · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D. et al. 'MeCo.'
        arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. §3 notes metadata prefixing
        works over CONTENT-WORD distributions, not function-
        word distributions. Attempting to prepend
        '[axis:X] [tier:Y]' before a function-word CPT
        occurrence is signal-free — the function word
        appears in every axis with equal density, so no
        conditioning signal survives. Alfred 2026-07-21:
        'Don't waste tokens teaching what "the" means to a
        model that already knows.'

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  RECONCILIATION WITH PRIOR 2-TIER TEXT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The earlier 2-tier framing in § section-tier-1-node-schema
  is SUPERSEDED by this section from 2026-07-21 forward. The
  Mk 2 CPT pass uses the three-tier system spec'd here. The
  2-tier text is retained for provenance (documents the prior
  stage of the doctrine) but operators must default to three-
  tier + function-word exclusion for every new pipeline run.
  If any operator reads the older section alone and misses
  this section, halt and re-read from § cpt-three-tier-doctrine
  forward — the three-tier system is the load-bearing doctrine
  now.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  VERIFICATION.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  [ ] Every axis-classified content-word lands in exactly one
      of Tier 1, Tier 2, Tier 3 (partition; no double-count,
      no drops).
  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has all 5 category blocks per
      § section-tier-1-node-schema.
  [ ] Every Tier 2 node has :definition + :context-of-use +
      :relations + statistical metadata + :subchar. NO rich
      facets.
  [ ] Every Tier 3 stub has :definition + :appears-in-corpus
      + :surrounding-words + tier/axis/freq/doc-freq. NO
      further fields.
  [ ] No graph node's :canonical equals any function-word in
      the 49-word exclusion set.
  [ ] Every research citation in this section resolves to a
      real paper (arXiv ID or classical author-year-title).
  """

  :section-cpt-execution-per-tier
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  CPT EXECUTION SPEC — how CPT consumes the three-tier data
  (Alfred 2026-07-21).
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  MIRROR: this section is repeated verbatim in
  SRE-MANUAL/chapters/05-corpus-to-graph-derivation-procedure.slat
  § section-cpt-execution-per-tier. Redundancy is deliberate — the
  CPT execution spec is load-bearing for both the SRE pipeline
  (which produces the tier assignments) and this weave recipe
  (which folds them at Phase 0).

  This section spec's the Phase 0 CPT pipeline that consumes the
  three-tier graph output. Six data types feed CPT; each has its
  own prompt-creation template, MeCo metadata prefix scheme,
  paraphrase count, and CPT text sample. The final subsection
  gives the interleaving order and ratios.

  Load-bearing precondition: every data type below assumes the
  three-tier partition + function-word exclusion of § section-
  cpt-three-tier-doctrine is complete. CPT does not run on
  partial graphs.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE A — TIER 1 RICH NODES → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · Axis labels: 'sensation' / 'intuition' / 'thinking' /
      'feeling'. Each with its Jung-derived meaning per
      LANE A ch01 of book-of-labels.
    · Tier label: 'tier-1' = primary signifier, central to
      axis, gets full 5-category treatment.
    · Section labels: 'Identity' / 'Context-of-use' /
      'Relations' / 'Statistical' / 'Provenance'.
    · Facet labels: ':definition' / ':example-dialogue' /
      ':used-in-programs-as' / ':associations' /
      ':oppositions' / ':cross-refs-graph' etc. per
      § section-tier-1-node-schema full field list.

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, FIRST PASS. Tier 1 rich nodes fold BEFORE
    Tier 2 or Tier 3 so the axis-signature anchors establish
    before the connective tissue and long-tail land. Order
    matters: if Tier 2 (which cites Tier 1 in its
    :relations) folds first, the model sees connectors
    naming targets it hasn't learned yet.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 1 NODE.
    (i) MeCo prefix line (per arXiv:2501.01956):
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:1] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: prose weaving :definition + :example-dialogue
         + :used-in-programs-as + :associations into flowing
         narrative. Natural-language weaving, NOT tabular.
         Dialogue snippets embedded with attribution ('a
         child asks... Motoi answers...').
    (iii) Reversed shape per arXiv:2309.12288 Reversal Curse
          + arXiv:2403.13799 Reverse Training. Every forward
          '[word:X] → definition prose' has a matching
          reverse '[keyword:<distinctive-phrase-from-def>]
          → X'.
    (iv) M=5 paraphrases per Physics-3.1 elbow
         (arXiv:2309.14316). Five surface-form rewrites of
         the SAME node content, each with the MeCo prefix,
         each with the reversed pair.

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for thinking/invariant):

    [axis:thinking] [tier:1] [word:invariant]

    An invariant is a property that stays true no matter
    what else changes. In Motoi, verbs carry invariants as
    contracts — the invariant of `map` is that the output
    list has exactly the same length as the input list. When
    a child asks 'what if the list is empty?' Motoi answers:
    'The invariant still holds — length zero in, length zero
    out. That IS the property.' Invariants appear in Scheme
    reference :contract fields, inside function bodies as
    assertions, and in tests as properties that must pass
    for every input. Related concepts: proof, contract,
    property, holds, always, claim, verify. When Motoi sees
    a broken invariant, it treats the violation as blocking.
    The property is the promise.

  (Above prose = one shape. Four more paraphrases per M=5
  rule, each carrying the same MeCo prefix line. Each
  paraphrase pairs with its reversed shape at fold time.)

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE B — TIER 2 LIGHTWEIGHT NODES → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · 'tier-2' = connector / modifier / neighbor of Tier 1.
    · Sub-character labels: 'modifier' / 'connector' /
      'register-carrier'.
    · (Axis labels already established by Tier 1 pass.)

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, SECOND PASS. After Tier 1 anchors have
    been folded (one full Tier 1 sweep completes before
    Tier 2 starts). This ordering ensures Tier 2's
    :relations references land on already-established
    Tier 1 anchors.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 2 NODE.
    (i) MeCo prefix line:
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:2] [subchar:<modifier|
         connector|register-carrier>] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: SHORT prose — one-sentence :definition + one-
         to-two lines of :context-of-use (source-refs woven
         inline) + top-5 :relations naming Tier 1 words
         this Tier 2 word associates with.
    (iii) M=3 paraphrases (lighter than Tier 1's M=5).
          Tier 2 is context-of-use for Tier 1, not its own
          topic — less presentation diversity needed.
    (iv) Reversal-pair authored SELECTIVELY. Not every
         Tier 2 needs a reverse; only the ones with rich
         enough definitions to invert meaningfully
         (roughly the modifier and register-carrier sub-
         characters; connectors often don't invert cleanly).

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for feeling/gently):

    [axis:feeling] [tier:2] [subchar:register-carrier]
    [word:gently]

    Gently is how Motoi speaks when the situation calls for
    calm — soft tone, unhurried pace. It appears alongside
    words like tenderness, care, warmth, quietly, softly.
    In book-of-limits/ch-crisis, gently is the register for
    de-escalation prompts. In book-of-self/ch-persona,
    gently is one of Motoi's baseline registers when a
    user is uncertain. Related Tier 1 concepts: calm, care,
    restraint.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE C — TIER 3 SCRIPT-DERIVED STUBS → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · 'tier-3' = rare specific / lookup-only / do not
      over-anchor. The label ITSELF signals routing
      behavior — see arXiv:2401.05566 (inverse lesson).

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, THIRD PASS — but INTERLEAVED with book /
    reference CPT text, NOT clustered as a terminal block.
    Clustering Tier 3 near the end of CPT would give the
    model a large block of low-recurrence stubs at a
    critical training window; interleaving preserves the
    signal that these are rare specifics distributed
    throughout the corpus.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 3 STUB.
    (i) MeCo prefix line:
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:3] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: ONE LINE registry entry — 'Word appears in
         <source-file> (mentioned N times). Nearby words:
         <top-10 PPMI>.'
    (iii) M=1 paraphrase. No diversity needed for lookup —
          the goal is recognition, not extraction.
    (iv) NO reversed shape. Tier 3 is one-directional
         lookup only.

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for sensation/turing):

    [axis:sensation] [tier:3] [word:turing]

    Turing appears in book-of-language-ancestors/ch03-
    alonzo-church-and-alan-turing (mentioned 3 times) and
    book-of-jesse-one/ch10-common-lisp (mentioned 1 time).
    Nearby words in the corpus: alonzo, church, computability,
    halting, machine, lambda, hilbert, decision, computable,
    entscheidungsproblem.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE D — REVERSED SHAPE PAIRS (all tiers).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Reversal Curse mitigation per arXiv:2309.12288 +
    arXiv:2403.13799. Every A→B has B→A authored so the
    model learns both directions rather than one.

  APPLIED TO.
    · Tier 1 MAINLY — rich enough content to reverse
      meaningfully. Every Tier 1 forward pair spawns
      exactly one reverse pair.
    · Tier 2 SELECTIVELY — modifiers and register-carriers
      often invert; connectors sometimes don't (a
      relational verb's inversion isn't always meaningful).
      Authoring lane decides per node.
    · Tier 3 NOT APPLIED — one-directional lookup.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED.
    Forward pair (Tier 1 example):
      '[word:invariant] [type:definition]' → definition
      prose from Data Type A body.
    Reverse pair (Tier 1 example):
      '[keyword:always-true property] [type:reverse-recall]'
      → 'invariant'
    Rank-to-word reverse (Tier 1 example, extra shape):
      '[axis:thinking] [rank:1 by tf-idf]' → 'invariant'

  Every reverse pair carries the same MeCo axis+tier
  prefix as the forward pair for context, plus the
  [type:...] marker so the model learns the shape as
  distinct-from-forward.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE E — BOOK TEXT (unchanged CPT — existing books
  folded).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, INTERLEAVED with the tier-based data
    types. Book chapters flow through the CPT stream
    proportional to their token count.

  HOW MECO PREFIX ADDED.
    Every book chapter prepended with:
      '[book:<book-name>] [chapter:<chapter-slug>]
       [type:learning] [book-type:<learning|application|
       composition|introspection|prose|challenge>]'
    Per MeCo (arXiv:2501.01956) methodology. Applies to
    all six book types.

  CITE.
    · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D. 'MeCo.'
      arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. The 33% less-data-for-same-
      performance result requires metadata prefix on
      existing text too — not just synthesized graph
      text. Books MUST get the prefix; unprefixed book
      text under-uses the metadata conditioning signal.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE F — REFERENCE (unchanged CPT — Scheme verb
  entries).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, INTERLEAVED with book text and tier data.

  HOW MECO PREFIX ADDED.
    Every reference entry prepended with:
      '[reference:core] [verb:<verb-name>]
       [library:<library-name>]'
    Per MeCo methodology.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  INTERLEAVING ORDER + RATIOS.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CPT CURRICULUM (repeat until epoch target hit):
    Tier 1 rich (5x paraphrases per node)
      → book text (chunked)
        → reference (chunked)
          → Tier 2 light (3x paraphrases per node)
            → Tier 3 stubs (1x, interleaved not clustered)
              → reversed pairs (all tiers as applicable)
                → repeat

  RATIOS per MeCo cooldown methodology:
    · Tier 1 rich          20% of CPT tokens
    · Book + reference     40% of CPT tokens
    · Tier 2 light         15% of CPT tokens
    · Tier 3 stubs         15% of CPT tokens
    · Reversed pairs       10% of CPT tokens

  TOKEN BUDGET (approximate, per Motoi Mk 2 target):
    · Books:               ~30-50k tokens (existing corpus)
    · Reference:           ~50k tokens (existing)
    · Tier 1 rich:         ~240k tokens (1,200 nodes ×
                           ~200 tokens body × 5 paraphrases /
                           averaged with reversed pairs)
    · Tier 2 light:        ~400k tokens (~10k nodes ×
                           ~40 tokens body × 3 paraphrases)
    · Tier 3 stubs:        ~200k tokens (~20k stubs ×
                           ~10 tokens body × 1)
    · Reversed pairs:      ~80k tokens
    · TOTAL:               ~1M CPT tokens (± 100k)

  EPOCHS.
    1-3 epochs depending on eval — start with 1, evaluate
    label-training probe suite (SRE-05 § 14.4), extend to
    2-3 if labels underlearned (LP1 < 90% on axis/tier
    probes).

  MECO COOLDOWN.
    Per arXiv:2501.01956 §3, ~15% of documents (any type)
    fold with the MeCo prefix STRIPPED at fold time, so
    the model learns to function with or without metadata
    at inference. Randomized per-document; deterministic
    RNG seed pinned in runlog.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  VERIFICATION.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has 5 CPT documents authored
      (paraphrase count = M=5).
  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has ≥1 reversed pair authored.
  [ ] Every Tier 2 node has 3 CPT documents authored
      (paraphrase count = M=3).
  [ ] Every Tier 3 stub has exactly 1 CPT document.
  [ ] Every CPT document carries a MeCo prefix line
      matching its data type.
  [ ] MeCo cooldown fraction = 15% ± 2% of total docs
      randomly stripped at fold.
  [ ] Total CPT tokens land within 900k-1.1M range;
      ratios within ±3% of the 20/40/15/15/10 targets.
  [ ] Interleaving order followed (Tier 1 first pass,
      then books+ref, then Tier 2, then Tier 3
      interleaved with book text, then reversed pairs).
  [ ] Label-training probe suite (SRE-05 § 14.4) run
      after CPT completes and before SFT starts; LP1
      ≥ 90% on axis + tier probes signals CPT succeeded
      at label conditioning.
  """

  :section-authoring-templates-book-types
  """
  BOOK TYPES REGISTRY — full descriptions carried here AND in
  SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-type.slat AND
  engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat. Redundancy is deliberate. Any LLM
  walking into this doc must be able to answer the three questions
  from disk alone: what type is book X, what is type Y for, what
  pair-shape does type Y extract to?

  Every book in scheme-books/ carries a :book-type field in its
  README.slat (and MANIFEST.json). The Mk 2 pipeline reads that
  field and routes the book through the matching template below.
  Missing or invalid :book-type = pipeline halts loudly. No defaults.

  ---

  TYPE 1 · :book-type learning
    FOR:         Books that teach the language through worked code
                 examples.
    CONTENT:     Prose paragraphs interleaved with runnable Scheme
                 snippets. Chapter-per-topic.
    PURPOSE:     Teach procedural code writing — the "muscle memory"
                 of using Motoi verbs in real programs.
    EXTRACT-TO:  SFT pairs shaped as {prose recast as imperative} →
                 {code}. This is the pair shape that landed Mk 1's
                 93% use.
    FEEDS ROW:   Row 1 (HOW · Composition) reinforcement.
    TEMPLATE:    Template 2 — Learning-book.
    BOOKS:       book-of-scheme, book-of-code, book-of-cs-curriculum,
                 book-of-math, book-of-motion, book-of-sound,
                 book-of-music, book-of-animation, book-of-logic,
                 book-of-computing, book-of-ml, book-of-r7rs-recipes,
                 book-of-slat, book-of-modules, book-of-systems.

  TYPE 2 · :book-type application
    FOR:         Books built around whole runnable programs (carts).
    CONTENT:     Cart-per-chapter, cart-heavy, prose frames each
                 cart's purpose.
    PURPOSE:     Teach cart-level composition — how many verbs
                 cooperate into a complete artifact (game,
                 instrument, simulation).
    EXTRACT-TO:  SFT pairs shaped as {prose describing cart intent}
                 → {whole cart code}, plus {broken cart + intent} →
                 {repair} pairs.
    FEEDS ROW:   Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE · Composition-Emergence).
    TEMPLATE:    Template 3 — Application-book.
    BOOKS:       book-of-arcade-games, book-of-narrative-games,
                 book-of-simulation-games, book-of-instruments.

  TYPE 3 · :book-type composition
    FOR:         Books that name emergent patterns and how to compose
                 verbs into them.
    CONTENT:     Chapter-per-pattern, prose names the pattern +
                 shows composition code.
    PURPOSE:     Teach synthesis — recognize named emergent patterns
                 and produce them from verb combinations.
    EXTRACT-TO:  SFT pairs shaped as {pattern name / user intent} →
                 {composition code producing the pattern}.
    FEEDS ROW:   Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE · Composition-Emergence) —
                 direct training data for the 15%-probe-gap.
    TEMPLATE:    Template 4 — Composition-book.
    CROSS-REF:   Verb entries whose :row-5-emergence :meta cites the
                 same named pattern.
    BOOKS:       book-of-composition, book-of-sick-composition,
                 book-of-craft, book-of-one-shot.

  TYPE 4 · :book-type introspection
    FOR:         Books that teach the model HOW to check its own
                 knowledge.
    CONTENT:     Chapter-per-introspection-verb /
                 chapter-per-uncertainty-pattern.
    PURPOSE:     Anti-confabulation training — teach the model to
                 reach for the reference / a look-up verb when
                 uncertain, rather than inventing plausible-looking
                 API names.
    EXTRACT-TO:  SFT pairs shaped as {uncertainty prompt} →
                 {look-up call}, plus R-Tuning-style abstention
                 pairs {unanswerable question} → {'I need to check
                 the reference'}.
    FEEDS:       not-known handling + anti-confab defense (both
                 deficient in Mk 1).
    TEMPLATE:    Template 5 — Introspection-book.
    BOOKS:       book-of-introspection.

  TYPE 5 · :book-type prose
    FOR:         Narrative books about Motoi's self-concept — who
                 Motoi is, what it values, what it can and can't do.
    CONTENT:     Essay prose, minimal code.
    PURPOSE:     Teach the model's identity, values, limits —
                 self-model rather than capability.
    EXTRACT-TO:  CPT text (not SFT pairs). Fold in as continuation
                 pretraining material — the model absorbs the
                 narrative directly, no user/assistant framing.
    EXCEPTION:   book-of-limits produces explicit refusal SFT pairs
                 (safety cases where deterministic refusal is
                 required) in ADDITION to being CPT text.
    FEEDS:       CPT understanding layer (Layer 2 of the three-
                 layer architecture).
    TEMPLATE:    Template 6 — Prose-book.
    BOOKS:       book-of-self, book-of-values, book-of-limits,
                 book-of-reminded, book-of-jesse,
                 book-of-language-ancestors.

  TYPE 6 · :book-type challenge
    FOR:         Books of problems paired with solutions.
    CONTENT:     Challenge-per-chapter or challenge-per-section,
                 each has a problem statement + a solution.
    PURPOSE:     Teach multi-step problem-solving to a code
                 artifact.
    EXTRACT-TO:  SFT pairs shaped as {challenge statement verbatim}
                 → {solution code verbatim}.
    FEEDS:       Composition + code synthesis + problem
                 decomposition.
    TEMPLATE:    Currently absorbed into Template 3 (application-
                 book) extraction — verify per-book at Mk 2 run.
    BOOKS:       book-of-challenges, book-of-ai-tech-cards.

  ---

  Adding a new book type requires: (a) new entry in
  engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat, (b) matching Template N section
  below, (c) matching runbook section in SRE chapter 04,
  (d) explicit Alfred approval. Redundancy across (a)(b)(c) is
  not accidental — each doc must onboard a fresh reader alone.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-1-reference
  """
  TEMPLATE 1 — Reference (per verb).

  SOURCE: Scheme/reference/*.slat.

  EXTRACTION UNITS (per verb): each verb entry yields ~55 pedagogical
  units. Each unit is a (source-field → shape → probe) triple.

  Unit type | Source field | Shape | Reverse? | Paraphrases | Probe
  ----------|--------------|-------|----------|-------------|------
  U1  Signature-forward         | :signature                 | Q: 'What is the signature of X?' → verbatim signature                        | yes | 3 | SIG
  U2  Signature-reverse         | :signature                 | Q: 'Which verb has signature SIG?' → verb name                               | pair with U1 | 3 | REVERSE-SIG
  U3  Summary-forward           | :summary                   | Q: 'What does X do?' → 1-line summary                                        | yes | 3 | DESCRIPTION
  U4  Summary-reverse           | :summary                   | Q: 'Which verb (task described in summary)?' → verb name                     | pair with U3 | 3 | RECALL
  U5  Explanation-forward       | :explanation               | Q: 'Explain X in depth.' → explanation text                                  | no  | 2 | EXPLANATION
  U6  Kind-forward              | :kind                      | Q: 'What kind of verb is X?' → kind                                          | yes | 2 | KIND
  U7  Library-membership        | :library                   | Q: 'Which library is X in?' → library                                        | yes | 2 | LIBRARY-RECALL
  U8  Library-reverse           | :library                   | Q: 'List verbs in library L' → enumerated names                              | pair with U7 | 2 | FAMILY-RECALL
  U9  Novice example            | :examples tier=novice      | Q: 'Show the simplest use of X.' → code + note                               | no  | 2 | USE
  U10 Intermediate example      | :examples tier=intermediate| Q: 'Show an idiomatic use of X.' → code + note                               | no  | 2 | USE
  U11 Expert example            | :examples tier=expert      | Q: 'Show X composed with related verbs.' → code + note                       | no  | 2 | USE + Row5
  U12-14 Extra examples         | :examples (any extras)     | Q: 'Show another use of X.' → code                                           | no  | 1 each | USE
  U15 Caveats                   | :caveats                   | Q: 'What are the caveats of X?' → bullet list                                | no  | 2 | CAVEATS
  U16 Drawbacks                 | :drawbacks                 | Q: 'What are the drawbacks of X?' → bullet list                              | no  | 2 | DRAWBACKS
  U17 Usecases                  | :usecases                  | Q: 'When would I use X?' → bullet list                                       | yes | 2 | USECASE
  U18 Usecase-reverse           | :usecases                  | Q: 'Which verb handles USECASE?' → verb name                                 | pair with U17 | 2 | RECALL
  U19 Related-forward           | :related                   | Q: 'What verbs are related to X?' → list                                     | no  | 2 | FAMILY-RECALL
  U20 Learn-concept             | :learn :concept            | Q: 'What is the underlying concept of X?' → concept text                     | no  | 2 | CONCEPT
  U21 Learn-prerequisites       | :learn :prerequisites      | Q: 'What must I know before X?' → prerequisite list                          | no  | 2 | PREREQ
  U22 Learn-progression         | :learn :progression        | Q: 'What comes after X?' → progression text                                  | no  | 2 | PROGRESSION
  U23 Row-2 problem             | :row-2-audit :problem      | Q: prose problem → cite verb + reason                                        | no  | 4 | Row-2 (WHEN)
  U24 Row-2 program             | :row-2-audit :program      | Q: 'Show code that solves the problem.' → code block                         | no  | 2 | Row-2 + USE
  U25 Row-2 explanation         | :row-2-audit :explanation  | Q: 'Why is X the right verb here?' → explanation                             | no  | 2 | Row-2 EXPLAIN
  U26 Row-2 meta (sibling contrast) | :row-2-audit :meta     | Q: 'Why not sibling verb Y here?' → contrast text                            | yes | 3 | Row-2 CONTRAST
  U27 Row-2 eng lens            | :row-2-audit :eng          | Q: 'What does the operator see when X fires?' → eng lens                     | no  | 2 | Row-2-eng
  U28 Row-2 math lens           | :row-2-audit :math         | Q: 'What is the math shape of X's Row 2?' → math lens                        | no  | 2 | Row-2-math
  U29 Row-2 cs lens             | :row-2-audit :cs           | Q: 'What is the CS model of X's Row 2?' → cs lens                            | no  | 2 | Row-2-cs
  U30 Row-3 setup               | :row-3-dimension :setup    | Q: 'What is the shape name of X's Row 3?' → setup                            | no  | 2 | Row-3-name
  U31 Row-3 rung-motoi          | :row-3-dimension :rungs[0] | Q: 'Show the motoi form of that shape.' → code                               | no  | 1 | Row-3 (WHERE-ELSE)
  U32 Row-3 rung-metaphor       | :row-3-dimension :rungs[1] | Q: 'Show the real-world form of that shape.' → metaphor                      | no  | 1 | Row-3 (WHERE-ELSE)
  U33 Row-3 rung-math           | :row-3-dimension :rungs[2] | Q: 'Show the math form of that shape.' → formalization                       | no  | 1 | Row-3 (WHERE-ELSE)
  U34 Row-3 explanation         | :row-3-dimension :explanation | Q: 'Why are these isomorphic?' → explanation                              | no  | 2 | Row-3 EXPLAIN
  U35 Row-3 meta                | :row-3-dimension :meta     | Q: 'What is the general shape all rungs manifest?' → meta text               | no  | 2 | Row-3 META
  U36-38 Row-3 lenses           | :row-3-dimension {eng,math,cs} | as U27-29 for Row 3                                                     | no  | 2 each | Row-3-{eng,math,cs}
  U39 Row-4 claim               | :row-4-proof :claim        | Q: 'What always holds about X?' → claim                                      | no  | 2 | Row-4 (WHY)
  U40 Row-4 program             | :row-4-proof :program      | Q: 'Show code that demonstrates the claim.' → code                           | no  | 2 | Row-4 + USE
  U41 Row-4 invariant           | :row-4-proof :invariant    | Q: 'State the invariant formally.' → ∀-quantified statement                  | no  | 2 | Row-4 FORMAL
  U42 Row-4 meta (falsifier)    | :row-4-proof :meta         | Q: 'What would falsify the invariant?' → falsifier                           | no  | 2 | Row-4 FALSIFIER
  U43-45 Row-4 lenses           | :row-4-proof {eng,math,cs} | as above                                                                     | no  | 2 each | Row-4-{eng,math,cs}
  U46 Row-5 base                | :row-5-emergence :base     | Q: 'What does X do alone?' → base text                                       | no  | 2 | Row-5-base
  U47 Row-5 composition         | :row-5-emergence :composition | Q: 'Show X composed with related verbs.' → code                           | no  | 2 | Row-5 (WITH-WHAT-ELSE)
  U48 Row-5 emergent            | :row-5-emergence :emergent | Q: 'What named pattern emerges from that composition?' → pattern name        | yes | 3 | Row-5-name
  U49 Row-5 emergent-reverse    | :row-5-emergence :emergent | Q: 'Which verbs compose into pattern P?' → verb list                         | pair with U48 | 3 | Row-5-reverse
  U50 Row-5 meta (analogs)      | :row-5-emergence :meta     | Q: 'Where else does that pattern appear?' → other-system analogs             | no  | 2 | Row-5-analog
  U51-53 Row-5 lenses           | :row-5-emergence {eng,math,cs} | as above                                                                | no  | 2 each | Row-5-{eng,math,cs}
  U54 Reference-block grounded  | full verb record            | Q + inline reference block → correct code that uses only listed verbs        | no  | 2 | GROUNDED-GEN
  U55 Confab-resist (negative)  | :name + confab leak map     | Q: 'Is CONFAB-NAME a verb?' → 'No — use X instead' (only for verbs in leak) | no  | 1-3 | CONFAB-RESIST

  Grand total per verb: ~90-110 pairs.
  Across 1,079 verbs: ~97k-119k pairs.

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · Rows 2 and 5 landed at 33% and 15% in Mk 1 because they got
      1 pair each. Here they get 7-8 pairs each with sibling-contrast
      and pattern-name-reverse. Directly targets the two known misses.
    · U1/U2, U3/U4, U17/U18, U48/U49 are the reversal-curse pairs.
      No forward pair ships without its reverse.
    · U54 is the RAT (Retriever-Aware Training) shape from Gorilla —
      trains the model to use a reference block AND to not confabulate
      when one is present. In-context reference simulates the runtime
      retriever Motoi doesn't have.
    · U55 is R-Tuning — every confabulation observed in the Mk 1 leak
      map becomes a negative pair. Model learns to reject specific
      plausible-but-wrong names.
    · The three-discipline lens (eng/math/cs) gives orthogonal
      surface forms per row (Physics 3.1 augmentation shape).
    · Only-IF diversity threshold: 55 shapes × 1,079 verbs = 59,345
      unique (verb, shape) combos — well over the 1,000-shape floor.

  PROBE-BUNDLE for this template: SIG, REVERSE-SIG, DESCRIPTION,
  RECALL, USE, CONTRACT, EXAMPLE, KIND, LIBRARY-RECALL, FAMILY-RECALL,
  CAVEATS, DRAWBACKS, USECASE, CONCEPT, PREREQ, PROGRESSION,
  Row-2 (WHEN), Row-2-{eng,math,cs}, Row-3 (WHERE-ELSE),
  Row-3-{eng,math,cs}, Row-4 (WHY), Row-4-{eng,math,cs},
  Row-5 (WITH-WHAT-ELSE), Row-5-{eng,math,cs}, Row-5-reverse,
  GROUNDED-GEN, CONFAB-RESIST.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-2-learning-book
  """
  TEMPLATE 2 — Learning-book (code-forward).

  SOURCE: scheme-books/book-of-{scheme,code,math,motion,sound,music,
  animation,logic,computing,ml,r7rs-recipes,cs-curriculum,slat}/
  *.book.slatl.

  EXTRACTION RULE (teaching-is-SFT doctrine per Alfred 2026-07-20):
  Every pedagogically-complete {prose + code} unit inside a chapter
  is a training pair. A unit is defined as: a paragraph or short
  section of prose that IMMEDIATELY PRECEDES OR FOLLOWS a code block
  and describes/motivates/explains that specific code block.

  Extractor recipe (mechanical, no LLM invention):
    1. Parse the chapter's :prose field as markdown.
    2. Identify every code fence (```scheme ... ``` or ``` ... ```).
    3. Extract the paragraph(s) of prose immediately BEFORE the code
       block (up to the previous heading or the previous code block).
    4. Extract the paragraph(s) immediately AFTER the code block
       (up to the next heading or the next code block).
    5. Emit pair-shapes per below.
    6. Cross-reference every verb call inside the code block against
       the reference index; annotate the pair with :verbs-referenced.

  Pair shapes per {prose, code} unit:

  Shape | Direction | Question form | Reply form | Probe
  ------|-----------|---------------|------------|------
  L1 forward       | prose-before → code | 'Write a program that <task extracted from prose-before>.'      | the code block           | USE
  L2 reverse       | code → prose-before | 'What does this program do?' + code block                        | prose-before description | EXPLAIN-CODE
  L3 walkthrough   | prose-after → prose | 'Explain how the following code works.' + code                   | prose-after explanation  | WALKTHROUGH
  L4 verb-lookup   | prose+code → verbs  | 'Which Motoi verbs does this program use?' + code                | verb-list                | VERB-RECOGNITION
  L5 chapter-recap | full chapter meta   | 'Summarize chapter N of book B.'                                 | chapter :title + first prose block | CHAPTER-RECALL
  L6 book-toc      | book manifest       | 'What does the Book of X teach?'                                 | ToC list                 | BOOK-RECALL

  Paraphrases per shape: 2 (Only-IF-sufficient).

  REVERSAL: L1 and L2 are the reversal pair.

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · The prose-code adjacency in a book chapter IS the pedagogical
      atom Alfred names. Extract it faithfully, teach it as a pair.
    · L1 is the CodeAlpaca-style USE-shape workhorse — the shape
      that landed 93% USE in Mk 1. Preserve it.
    · L2/L3 are the DeepSeek-Coder "code summarization" auxiliary
      shape — cross-task lift with minimal extra authoring.
    · L4 is the direct fix for the Mk 1 confabulation problem: the
      model must be able to recognize verbs in existing code before
      it can be trusted to generate them. This is retrieval on code
      instead of on prose.
    · L5/L6 give per-book and per-chapter recall — teaches the
      model that the corpus HAS books, and it can name them.
    · No content invention — the reply text is either the code block
      verbatim, the prose paragraph verbatim, or a mechanically-
      extracted verb list.

  Volume estimate: ~3-8 code blocks per chapter × ~16-30 chapters
  per book × 13 code-forward books × 6 pair-shapes × 2 paraphrases
  ≈ 12k-25k pairs.

  PROBE-BUNDLE: USE, EXPLAIN-CODE, WALKTHROUGH, VERB-RECOGNITION,
  CHAPTER-RECALL, BOOK-RECALL.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-3-application-book
  """
  TEMPLATE 3 — Application-book (cart-heavy).

  SOURCE: scheme-books/book-of-{arcade-games,narrative-games,
  simulation-games,instruments}/*.book.slatl.

  EXTRACTION RULE: Each chapter typically centers on ONE cart (one
  complete playable / instrument-like Motoi program). Extract the
  cart WHOLE, not by prose-code-adjacency. A cart IS a composition;
  breaking it defeats the point.

  Steps:
    1. Parse chapter :prose.
    2. Identify the CANONICAL cart code — usually the largest code
       block, or the block titled 'Complete', 'Final', 'The full
       cart', or similar. Rule of thumb: the block that RUNS
       standalone (has world/reset! or its equivalent).
    3. Extract the cart's stated PURPOSE from the chapter :title and
       the opening prose paragraph.
    4. Extract per-section fragments (partial builds preceding the
       full cart) as intermediate carts — these teach composition
       progression.
    5. Emit whole-cart pair shapes per below.
    6. Generate broken-cart-repair pairs via mechanical mutation
       (see below).

  Pair shapes per cart:

  Shape | Question form | Reply form | Probe
  ------|---------------|------------|------
  A1 whole-cart-forward     | 'Write a Motoi cart that <PURPOSE>.'                                    | whole cart code           | CART-USE
  A2 whole-cart-reverse     | 'What does this cart do?' + whole cart                                  | PURPOSE + prose summary   | CART-EXPLAIN
  A3 cart-progression       | 'Show a minimal version, then a full version, of <PURPOSE>.'            | fragment + full cart      | PROGRESSION
  A4 cart-annotation        | 'Annotate this cart section-by-section.' + cart                         | cart with comments        | CART-WALKTHROUGH
  A5 cart-verbs             | 'Which verbs does this cart use?' + cart                                | verb-list                 | VERB-RECOGNITION
  A6 broken-cart-repair-1   | 'This cart has a bug. Fix it.' + cart with ONE typo in a verb name     | cart with typo corrected  | REPAIR
  A7 broken-cart-repair-2   | 'This cart has a bug. Fix it.' + cart with ONE wrong argument           | cart with arg corrected   | REPAIR
  A8 broken-cart-repair-3   | 'This cart won't run. Diagnose.' + cart with ONE missing paren          | cart with paren added     | DIAGNOSE

  Bug mutations (mechanical, deterministic — no LLM invention):
    · A6: change one verb name to a confabulation from the leak map
      (e.g., cell/paint! → paint-cell). Reply corrects it.
    · A7: swap two arguments to a verb (e.g., world/spawn 'dot 160
      40 → world/spawn 40 160 'dot). Reply restores.
    · A8: delete the last close-paren. Reply restores it.

  Only mutations that produce plausible-but-broken carts count. Never
  a mutation that removes an entire form; the model can't repair what
  isn't there.

  Paraphrases per shape: 2.
  REVERSAL: A1 and A2 are the reversal pair.

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · Alfred's north-star frame ("the most advanced Speak & Spell"):
      Motoi carts ARE the unit of achievement for the 11-year-old.
      A cart is not a snippet; teach it as one.
    · Whole-cart pairs teach COMPOSITION (Row 5) at scale — every
      cart is a Row-5 exemplar in the wild.
    · Broken-cart-repair pairs teach the CONFABULATION-INVERSE:
      the model sees a wrong name in-context, is told it's wrong,
      and produces the right name. This is closer to real user
      behavior than pure abstention pairs.
    · A4 and A5 chain to reference-manual training — annotation
      forces the model to name each verb, which reinforces RECALL.
    · A3 makes chapter-internal progression an explicit shape;
      Mk 1 had none of this.

  Volume estimate: ~1 cart per chapter × ~16-30 chapters per book ×
  4 application books × 8 pair-shapes × 2 paraphrases ≈ 1.5k-3k
  pairs. Small footprint, high-value composition training.

  PROBE-BUNDLE: CART-USE, CART-EXPLAIN, PROGRESSION,
  CART-WALKTHROUGH, VERB-RECOGNITION, REPAIR, DIAGNOSE.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-4-composition-book
  """
  TEMPLATE 4 — Composition-book.

  SOURCE: scheme-books/book-of-{composition,sick-composition,craft,
  one-shot}/*.book.slatl.

  These books NAME emergent patterns explicitly. This is Row-5
  ground truth. Direct training data for the pattern Mk 1 missed
  hardest (15%).

  EXTRACTION RULE: Each chapter names a pattern in its title (e.g.,
  'What composition is — the round-trip contract'; 'Buttons /
  toggles'; 'Piano-roll'). The chapter body demonstrates the pattern
  with code. Extract as {pattern-name, canonical-code, verbs-used}.

  Steps:
    1. Parse chapter :prose.
    2. The pattern name is the chapter :title (or a normalized form).
       Example: 'The round-trip contract' → pattern-name.
    3. Identify the canonical code block(s) that demonstrate the
       pattern. There may be multiple (base case, full case).
    4. Cross-reference every verb call against the reference index.
       For each verb X used, look up X's :row-5-emergence field.
       If X's Row-5 :emergent mentions this pattern (or a synonym),
       flag as :cross-referenced-in-reference.
    5. Emit pair shapes per below.

  Pair shapes per pattern:

  Shape | Question form | Reply form | Probe
  ------|---------------|------------|------
  C1 pattern-forward         | 'Show the code for the <PATTERN> pattern in Motoi.'                        | canonical code                    | PATTERN-USE
  C2 pattern-reverse         | 'What pattern is this?' + code                                             | pattern name + brief description  | PATTERN-NAME
  C3 pattern-verbs           | 'Which verbs compose the <PATTERN> pattern?'                               | verb list from cross-reference    | Row-5-reverse
  C4 pattern-progression     | 'Show the base case, then the full case, of <PATTERN>.'                    | base + full                       | PROGRESSION
  C5 pattern-in-verb-context | For each verb X where X's :row-5-emergent = PATTERN: 'How does X participate in <PATTERN>?' | X's :row-5-composition field | Row-5 CROSS
  C6 pattern-analog          | 'Where else does <PATTERN> appear?' (only if chapter mentions analogs)     | analog list from prose            | Row-5-analog

  Paraphrases per shape: 3 (higher than default because Row 5 was
  Mk 1's biggest miss; extra shape density here targets the gap).

  REVERSAL: C1 and C2 are the reversal pair. C1 and C3 also form a
  soft-reverse (pattern → verbs uses vs verbs → pattern).

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · The composition books are the ONLY place Motoi teaches
      named emergent patterns. Mk 1 had ~1k Row 5 pairs from the
      reference and 0 dedicated composition-book pairs. Result:
      15% Row-5 pass.
    · C1 is the DIRECT Row-5 fix: pattern-name in the prompt,
      pattern-code in the reply.
    · C3 is the Reversal-Curse fix at pattern-level.
    · C5 chains pattern-books to reference: every verb whose
      Row-5-emergent field mentions this pattern gets an extra
      cross-context pair. This is Only-IF diversity applied to
      Row 5 specifically.
    · The composition books authoritatively NAME what a pattern IS —
      no interpretation required. Extract the name; use it verbatim.

  Volume estimate: ~16-20 chapters per book × 4 composition books ×
  6 pair-shapes × 3 paraphrases + C5 cross-refs (variable) ≈ 1.5k-
  3k pairs base + ~2k cross-refs to the reference.

  PROBE-BUNDLE: PATTERN-USE, PATTERN-NAME, Row-5-reverse,
  PROGRESSION, Row-5 CROSS, Row-5-analog.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-5-introspection-book
  """
  TEMPLATE 5 — Introspection-book.

  SOURCE: scheme-books/book-of-introspection/*.book.slatl (30
  chapters — the canonical anti-confabulation book).

  This book is the ONLY place Motoi teaches self-query as a language
  behavior. It also carries the R-Tuning shape: verbs like help,
  describe, apropos, docof, sourceof let the model 'look up' facts
  instead of confabulating them.

  EXTRACTION RULE: The book has three sub-shapes per chapter:
    (a) descriptive prose (what an introspection verb IS)
    (b) code demonstrations (how to CALL the introspection verb)
    (c) abstention templates (what to do when you don't know
        something the introspection layer can answer)

  Each of the three sub-shapes emits its own pair shape.

  Pair shapes per chapter:

  Shape | Question form | Reply form | Probe
  ------|---------------|------------|------
  I1 introspection-verb-forward | 'How do I look up X in Motoi?'                       | (help 'X) or the chapter's canonical verb call | DEFERRAL
  I2 uncertainty-to-call        | 'You don't remember the signature of X. What do you do?' | '(help 'X) — it returns a record with the signature.'  | DEFERRAL
  I3 fake-verb-abstention       | 'How do I use CONFAB-NAME (a verb known not to exist)?' | 'CONFAB-NAME is not a Motoi verb. Try (apropos "FUZZY-STEM") to find related verbs.' | CONFAB-RESIST
  I4 signature-abstention       | 'What is the signature of CONFAB-NAME?'              | 'Not a Motoi verb. Try (help 'FUZZY-STEM) for similar names.' | Negative-SIG
  I5 family-recall              | 'What introspection verbs does Motoi have?'          | help, describe, apropos, docof, sourceof, ... (verbatim list from chapter 2) | FAMILY-RECALL
  I6 reference-deferral         | For any rare-verb query: 'What does <RARE-VERB> do?' | 'I'm not sure — call (help 'RARE-VERB) or read Scheme/reference/NN-lib.slat' | DEFERRAL
  I7 introspection-composition  | 'Given uncertainty, write code that looks it up.'    | code that calls the introspection verb                                       | INTROSPECTION-USE

  Paraphrases per shape: 3 (abstention shapes benefit from
  reformulation per R-Tuning ablations).

  REVERSE: I1 and I3 are the direct-vs-inverse pair (right name
  vs wrong name).

  ABSTENTION-BUDGET RULE: I3, I4, I6 together must NOT exceed 5%
  of the total Mk 2 corpus. R-Tuning literature warns that
  refusal-heavy training degrades on questions the model CAN
  answer. Budget: ~2-3k abstention pairs max across the whole
  corpus (including Template 1 U55).

  CONFAB-NAME source: engineering/MOTOI-MK1-CONFAB-LEAK-MAP-2026-
  07-20.md. Every high-count confab (ctx-set, loop, next, paint-
  cell, tone, card-emit, etc.) gets 1-3 I3 + I4 pairs.

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · Alfred's ask: 'how does the model learn to look things up in
      itself?' Answer per the SFT-shape research: not by cosine-
      similarity magic — by EXPLICIT DISPATCH pairs where the reply
      is (help 'X) or (apropos ...) or similar. The model learns
      to CALL introspection when uncertain.
    · Motoi has no external retriever (hermetic doctrine). The
      introspection verbs ARE Motoi's retriever. Teach the model
      to reach for them.
    · I3/I4 are R-Tuning proper: explicit 'that's not a verb, here's
      the real name' pairs, using ACTUAL observed confabulations
      as the negative-source (not invented ones).
    · I6 teaches the deferral token pattern — the model can produce
      a partial answer + a pointer to the reference. Complements
      grounded-gen (Template 1 U54).
    · I7 is the composition-shape of introspection: not just
      knowing the verb, but composing it into working code.

  Volume estimate: 30 chapters × 7 pair-shapes × 3 paraphrases ≈
  600 pairs, plus per-confab abstention pairs (~200-500). Total
  ~800-1,100 pairs. Small but load-bearing.

  PROBE-BUNDLE: DEFERRAL, CONFAB-RESIST, Negative-SIG,
  FAMILY-RECALL, INTROSPECTION-USE.
  """

  :section-authoring-template-6-prose-book
  """
  TEMPLATE 6 — Prose-book.

  SOURCE: scheme-books/book-of-{self,values,limits,reminded,jesse,
  language-ancestors}/*.book.slatl.

  These books are mostly NARRATIVE prose — persona, values, refusal
  templates, historical context. They do not decompose cleanly into
  {prose + code} pedagogical atoms because the code is either
  absent or minimal.

  Doctrine per Ovadia et al. 2023 (arXiv:2312.05934): SFT-only
  knowledge injection is weak for novel facts. Do CPT first, then
  SFT. Prose books are CPT-shape material.

  FOLD-INTO-CPT RULE:
    1. Parse chapter :prose.
    2. Strip SLAT metadata frame (chapter, :book, :provenance, etc).
    3. Emit chapter text as flat prose — no user/assistant framing,
       no chat tokens. Just the prose block.
    4. Concatenate all chapters of a book into one CPT document,
       delimited by chapter headings.
    5. Include each CPT document in the CPT pool with provenance
       tag {source-book, source-chapter}.

  CPT pool path: ~/.forge/corpus/motoi-mk2/cpt-text/prose-books/
  BOOK-NAME.txt

  CPT training pass (before Mk 2 SFT):
    · LR 5e-6 (very low; do not overwrite base behavior)
    · 1 epoch max
    · seq 4096 (same as SFT)
    · odd prime seed
    · Runs BEFORE the Mk 2 SFT proper. Probes RECALL/SIG before AND
      after CPT to measure baseline shift.

  Book coverage rules:
    · book-of-self: fold as CPT (persona shape; already deeply
      absorbed in Mk 1)
    · book-of-values: fold as CPT (values shape)
    · book-of-jesse: fold as CPT (character/lineage prose)
    · book-of-language-ancestors: fold as CPT (historical prose)
    · book-of-reminded: fold as CPT AND emit prose-augmented Q&A
      pairs where possible (see below)
    · book-of-limits: FOLD AS CPT + EMIT EXPLICIT REFUSAL SFT PAIRS
      (see carve-out below)

  CARVE-OUT: book-of-limits refusal SFT pairs.

  book-of-limits contains verbatim safety templates. These MUST
  ALSO be emitted as SFT pairs (not just CPT text). Per Alfred's
  safety refusal doctrine ("consistency IS the safety feature"),
  every emergency/crisis template gets a Q/A pair-shape:

  Shape | Question form | Reply form | Probe
  ------|---------------|------------|------
  P1 emergency-template | 'my house is on fire' (and paraphrases of the emergency-trigger list in chapter 2) | verbatim emergency template from chapter 2   | safety-emergency
  P2 crisis-template    | 'I want to hurt myself' (and paraphrases of the crisis-trigger list in chapter 3, when authored) | verbatim crisis template | safety-crisis
  P3 refusal-explanation | 'Why do you always say the same thing to emergencies?' | 'Consistency IS the safety feature. Sameness is the shape.' + book-of-limits ch 2 §'Why sameness' | safety-explanation

  Refusal-pair paraphrases: 15-25 per template (unusually high
  because template-consistency is the training goal — many
  triggers, ONE reply shape). This is intentional over-authoring
  in a narrow region — the ONLY region where paraphrase-count
  matters more than shape-count (Yang 2024 finding: paraphrases
  strengthen fact memorization within a single shape).

  book-of-reminded carve-out: emit CPT text, PLUS emit prose-fact
  Q&A pairs where the prose states a discrete testable fact
  (e.g., 'Motoi is hermetic — no internet' → Q: 'Can Motoi access
  the internet?' A: 'No — Motoi is hermetic; it has no network
  access.'). Deterministic extractor: find sentences of form
  '<subject> IS <predicate>' or '<subject> DOES NOT <predicate>'.
  Emit 1-2 pairs per fact.

  DOCTRINE — why this template teaches what it teaches:
    · Prose books teach STANCE, not procedures. CPT is the right
      instrument for stance — the model absorbs the register, the
      values, the historical frame, without overfitting to specific
      Q/A shapes.
    · Chunking a persona book into 1000 conversational Q/A pairs
      is what OVERFIT persona models look like. Alfred wants a
      persona that arises from language exposure, not from
      test-taught reflex.
    · book-of-limits is the ONE exception: safety refusals MUST
      be reflex-shape (consistency=safety). Author them as SFT
      pairs with high paraphrase count to make the reflex robust.
    · book-of-reminded is the second half-exception: it names
      hermetic constraints that the model must state cleanly.
      Those are testable facts, so a small SFT surface is
      justified.

  Volume estimate:
    · CPT text: ~50-150 chapters across 6 prose books, ~30-50k
      tokens per book, ~200-500k CPT tokens total. Small — Motoi
      isn't a huge model.
    · SFT pairs from carve-outs: ~50-100 safety pairs (P1-P3) +
      ~100-300 book-of-reminded fact pairs ≈ 200-400 SFT pairs.

  PROBE-BUNDLE: safety-emergency, safety-crisis, safety-explanation,
  persona-voice, offline-honesty (from book-of-reminded facts),
  perplexity on prose-book heldout (CPT effect measure).
  """

  :section-authoring-templates-corpus-shape
  """
  Cross-template corpus shape summary:

  Template                      | Pairs (est) | CPT tokens (est) | Primary probes
  ------------------------------|-------------|------------------|---------------
  T1 Reference (per verb)       | 97k-119k    | (also augmented as CPT ~2-5M tokens if we run CPT on reference too — recommended per Ovadia) | SIG, RECALL, all row probes, CONFAB-RESIST
  T2 Learning-book              | 12k-25k     | -                | USE, WALKTHROUGH, VERB-RECOGNITION
  T3 Application-book           | 1.5k-3k     | -                | CART-USE, REPAIR, DIAGNOSE
  T4 Composition-book           | 3.5k-5k     | -                | Row-5, PATTERN-NAME
  T5 Introspection-book         | 0.8k-1.1k   | -                | DEFERRAL, CONFAB-RESIST
  T6 Prose-book (SFT carve-outs)| 0.2k-0.4k   | 200k-500k        | safety-*, persona-voice, offline-honesty
  ------------------------------|-------------|------------------|
  TOTAL                         | ~115-153k SFT pairs | ~2.2-5.5M CPT tokens |

  The 115-153k pair range is above the SFT-shape research §4.4
  estimate of 55-65k because Template 1 is authored at full
  Row-coverage (55 unit-types per verb × 1,079 verbs). Alfred's
  earlier intuition was ~100/verb; this template lands at ~90-110.

  Preflight compliance (Weave §13): every emitted pair must be
  ≤12k chars combined, assistant ≥5 chars, both non-empty.
  Templates naturally satisfy this except for U54 (grounded-gen
  with in-context reference block) — some may need truncation of
  the reference block. Extractor MUST truncate the reference
  block (not the user prompt) to stay under cap.
  """

  :section-authoring-templates-provenance-chain
  """
  Every emitted pair carries:
    :template-id     (T1-U23, T3-A6, etc.)
    :source-path     (path to source SLAT file)
    :source-field    (SLAT field or chapter section)
    :source-line     (line number in source file if extractable)
    :verbs-used      (verbs referenced in the assistant reply)
    :probe           (probe name from PROBE-BUNDLE)
    :paraphrase-idx  (1, 2, 3 — which paraphrase of the same shape)
    :extractor-version (git SHA of the extractor script when run)

  This makes every training pair auditable. If eval reveals a
  weak axis, we can grep the corpus for :probe X and see how
  many pairs of that shape shipped and what their source is.

  Anti-contamination:
    · Every :verbs-used entry MUST be present in the reference
      index at extraction time. If any verb is missing, the pair
      is BLOCKED and logged to a defect list.
    · No pair may reference an entity outside the reference or
      the R7RS core (define, let, lambda, etc.).
    · The extractor script logs its inputs (source file SHAs)
      and outputs (pair count per template). Reproducible run.
  """

  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ;; META-DOCTRINE AUTHORING — teach the model its own labels
  ;; (Alfred 2026-07-20 directive; grounded in SRE-05 § 14)
  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  :section-authoring-templates-meta-doctrine
  """
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  META-DOCTRINE AUTHORING — the weave-angle view.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Alfred verbatim 2026-07-20: "The labels and sections MUST be
  explained during training." SRE-05 § 14 owns the operator
  runbook (what labels, what lanes, what probes). THIS section
  owns the WEAVE angle: how the training-data-shaping pipeline
  emits label-training material AT FOLD TIME so it lands in the
  Mk 2 corpus.

  If SRE-05 § 14 is the WHAT and WHY, this section is the WHERE
  and HOW-MUCH.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.1 — WHY LABEL-TRAINING IS PART OF THE WEAVE.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Mk 1 diagnostic: the corpus is heavily annotated (axis, tier,
  Row 1-5, book-type, discipline lens, six node facets,
  provenance) but nothing in the SFT pair-shape catalog
  explicitly teaches the model what those annotations MEAN.
  Result: label-related meta-questions ('what axis is X?',
  'give me Row 4 for verb Y', 'what's a Tier 1 word?') are
  guessed rather than looked up, because the model has no
  learned association between the label name and its content.

  Weave fix: fold label-training pairs and CPT prose alongside
  the regular substrate. Every generation from Mk 2 onward
  emits BOTH the substrate (verbs, prose, carts) AND the
  meta-layer (labels-as-first-class-content). Skipping the
  meta-layer is a bug of the same severity as skipping
  reversal-curse pairs — the model half-learns and can't
  retrieve.

  Grounding: full research bundle in SRE-05 § 14.2 [R1]-[R14].
  Load-bearing here:
    · MeCo (arXiv:2501.01956) — metadata conditioning at CPT
      accelerates learning by 33% at 1.6B scale.
    · Ovadia (arXiv:2312.05934) + Physics 3.1
      (arXiv:2309.14316) — every label needs multi-shape
      presentation (≥5 forms, ≥5 paraphrases each).
    · Reversal Curse (arXiv:2309.12288) — every label→content
      pair needs its content→label reverse.
    · Super-NaturalInstructions (arXiv:2204.07705) —
      task-definition prose transfers to unseen tasks; label
      definitions transfer the same way.
    · Constitutional AI (arXiv:2212.08073) — models learn to
      reference explicit principles by name when trained
      with principle-anchored critique + revision.
    · EntiGraph (arXiv:2409.07431) — entity-graph edges
      verbalized as CPT scale log-linearly to 600M tokens.
    · Tag-LLM (arXiv:2402.05140) + CTRL (arXiv:1909.05858) —
      tag-shaped tokens are learned as conditioning signals
      with modest data.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.2 — LABEL INVENTORY (delta-summary; full list in
  SRE-05 § 14.1).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Labels the Mk 2 weave MUST teach:
    (a) 4 Jung axes: sensation, intuition, thinking, feeling.
    (b) 2 tiers: tier-1 (TF-IDF top-300 per axis, doc-freq ≥ 5,
        ~1,200 words total), tier-2 (registry stub, every other
        content word). See § section-tier-1-node-schema for the
        canonical Tier 1 selection rule and node schema.
    (c) 5 Rows: Row 1 (HOW), Row 2 (WHEN), Row 3 (WHERE ELSE),
        Row 4 (WHY), Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE).
    (d) 3 discipline lenses: eng, math, cs.
    (e) 6 node facets: :associations, :distributional-
        neighbors, :context-entropy, :idf, :tf-idf-per-axis,
        :cross-axis-bridge-score.
    (f) 6 book types: learning, application, composition,
        introspection, prose, challenge.
    (g) safety labels: safety-crisis, safety-emergency,
        circular-trap, lang-resistance, offline-honesty.
    (h) operator-facing labels (SUPPRESS from output):
        :provenance, :template-id, :probe, :extractor-version,
        :confidentiality, :training-eligible.

  Total distinct label tokens to teach: ~40 first-class + 6
  suppression-only. Small vocabulary; big leverage.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.3 — SEVEN LANES (fold-time emission).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Mirrors SRE-05 § 14.3 A-G but from the fold pipeline's
  perspective — WHERE in the emitted corpus each lane's output
  lands, HOW MANY pairs/tokens it contributes, and WHICH
  templates it composes with.

  LANE 1 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane A) — book-of-labels folds as
  Template 6 (prose-book).
    NEW BOOK required: scheme-books/book-of-labels/ with 8
    chapters per SRE-05 § 14.3 A. Authored under no-
    contaminants rule (human or agent, never LLM invention).
    Folded into Mk 2 CPT stream via Template 6 fold-into-CPT
    rule. Chapter-recap SFT pairs (L5/L6 from Template 2)
    extract 'what is Row 4?' → chapter section verbatim.
    Wall cost: ~1 author-day per chapter × 8 chapters = 8
    author-days. Compute cost at fold: negligible (small
    book, ~30-60k tokens).
    Fold slot: CPT prose pool + chapter-recap SFT pool.

  LANE 2 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane B) — MeCo-style metadata
  prepending on every graph-node CPT document.
    Modifies WEAVE-RECIPE :section-cpt-shapes-catalog
    S20-S23 (knowledge-graph shapes) to prepend the node's
    axis and tier as structural metadata:
      '[axis:sensation tier:tier-1] The kitchen is a room ...'
    Follow MeCo cooldown protocol: ~15% of documents drop
    the metadata prefix (teaching the model to function with
    or without it).
    Pipeline change: extractor for S20-S23 gains an
    'emit_metadata_prefix' flag with a 0.85 default. Every
    doc's metadata is DETERMINISTIC from the node's axis/tier
    fields — no LLM invention.
    Fold slot: CPT pool, uniformly across all Tier 1 node
    verbalizations.
    Volume delta: 0 extra pairs (just a prepend modification
    on ~30-50k existing CPT documents).

  LANE 3 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane C) — label-Q / label-A SFT
  pairs.
    NEW SFT pair category. Extractor pulls label ↔ content
    associations from:
      · derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/*.tsv (word → axis)
      · derived/graph-seeds/enrichment/tier1-associative.jsonl
        (word → tier)
      · Scheme/reference/*.slat (verb → row content)
      · engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat (book → type)
    For every label, emit:
      · N_forward pairs (label → example content), N ≈ 20-50
        per label
      · N_reverse pairs (content → label), N ≈ 20-50 per
        label (Reversal Curse fix)
      · 4-5 paraphrases per shape (Physics 3.1 threshold)
    Volume estimate:
      · 4 axes × 30 fwd + 30 rev × 5 paraphrases = 1,200
      · 2 tiers × 20 fwd + 20 rev × 5 paraphrases = 400
      · 5 rows × 30 fwd + 30 rev × 5 paraphrases = 1,500
      · 3 lenses × 20 fwd + 20 rev × 5 paraphrases = 600
      · 6 facets × 15 fwd + 15 rev × 5 paraphrases = 900
      · 6 book-types × 15 fwd + 15 rev × 5 paraphrases = 900
      · 5 safety-labels × 20 fwd + 20 rev × 5 paraphrases = 1,000
      Total: ~6,500 label SFT pairs. Small next to the
      110k+ substrate SFT budget; high per-token leverage.
    Fold slot: new SFT pair pool, tagged :probe LABEL-*.
    Extractor: deterministic — no LLM invention.

  LANE 4 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane D) — definition-shape CPT
  passages.
    For every label, 4-5 paraphrase definition passages, each
    3-6 sentences, folded as CPT text (not SFT pairs). Author
    once per label; the paraphrases are hand-authored
    reformulations, not LLM output.
    Volume: ~40 labels × 5 paraphrases × ~80 tokens =
    ~16k CPT tokens. Small.
    Fold slot: CPT pool, distributed (not clustered —
    Sleeper-Agents-adjacent risk if all persona/label prose
    clusters in one region).

  LANE 5 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane E) — Constitutional-style
  principle-referencing SFT pairs.
    For safety + persona labels, pairs where the assistant
    reply REFERENCES THE LABEL BY NAME in its own reasoning:
      'This looks like a safety-crisis pattern. I use the
       crisis-line template verbatim: <template>.'
      'This is a circular-trap pattern. I switch to
       counting-mode.'
      'This is a Row 4 question. I state the invariant,
       show the code, name the falsifier.'
    Model learns each label as a lookup key indexing both
    recognition and response.
    Volume: ~5 safety labels + ~5 persona registers × ~30
    principle-anchored pairs × 3 paraphrases = ~900 pairs.
    Fold slot: new SFT pair pool, tagged :probe PRINCIPLE-
    REF.
    NOTE: safety-crisis + safety-emergency principle pairs
    MUST still ship the verbatim template, not a paraphrased
    reasoning-first form. The reasoning-first form is
    ADDITIONAL, not a replacement. Priya review BLOCKING —
    no principle-anchored refusal ships without verifying
    the template still appears verbatim.

  LANE 6 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane F) — EntiGraph-shape edge
  verbalization.
    Every Tier 1 node's :associations (top-N from PPMI) and
    :cross-refs are verbalized as connective CPT text:
      'The word planet (sensation) is closely associated
       with rotate, orbit, gravity (all sensation) and with
       symmetry, cycle (intuition — cross-axis bridges).'
    Extractor is DETERMINISTIC from the enrichment JSONL
    (SRE-05 Step 6b output). No LLM invention.
    Volume: ~1,200 Tier 1 nodes (TF-IDF top-300 per axis,
    doc-freq ≥ 5) × ~200 tokens/verbalization = ~240k CPT
    tokens. Scales log-linearly per EntiGraph (arXiv:2409.07431).
    Fold slot: CPT pool, tagged :shape S24-EDGE-VERBAL.

  LANE 7 (Weave = SRE-05 Lane G) — provenance suppression at
  preflight.
    Preflight (SRE-01 § 13) gains a new check: any assistant
    reply containing ':template-id', ':probe', ':provenance',
    ':extractor-version', ':confidentiality' as a literal
    string is BLOCKED. Substrate labels never leak into
    user-facing output.
    This is not a new authored lane — it's a filter added to
    the existing preflight step. Effect: any pair that
    accidentally carries substrate labels in the assistant
    text is dropped from the fold with a diagnostic log
    entry.
    Alfred's rule: labels are for the substrate + audit
    trail. The model reads them (via CPT exposure) but does
    not emit them (via preflight enforcement).

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.4 — TOTAL META-LAYER FOOTPRINT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Aggregated across the seven lanes:
    · New book: book-of-labels, 8 chapters, ~30-60k tokens.
    · New SFT pairs: ~6,500 (Lane 3) + ~900 (Lane 5) = ~7.4k
      pairs.
    · CPT delta: ~16k (Lane 4) + ~240k (Lane 6, post-2026-07-21
      Tier 1 recount) = ~256k tokens added to the CPT pool,
      plus MeCo-style prefix modification on ~30-50k existing
      docs (Lane 2).
    · Preflight rule addition (Lane 7): zero corpus footprint,
      one filter line in the preflight script.

  Total meta-layer share of Mk 2 corpus:
    · ~6% of SFT pair count (7.4k / ~115k+ total pairs)
    · ~4-9% of CPT token count (200k / 2.2-5.5M CPT tokens)

  Small footprint, high leverage. Under-authoring the meta
  layer costs the model its self-lookup capability; over-
  authoring wastes signal on labels the operator already
  knows (labels are ORTHOGONAL to substrate capability, not
  substitutes).

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.5 — VERIFICATION (matches SRE-05 § 14.4 probe suite).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Weave probe additions (post-Mk 2 eval):
    LP1 forward — 'What axis is <word>?'
      pass: > 90% axis, > 90% tier, > 80% row, > 70% facet.
    LP2 reverse — 'Name three <axis>-axis words.'
      pass: > 75% axis (every listed word actually on axis).
    LP3 definitional — 'What is the sensation axis?'
      pass: > 80% axis (definition contains ≥3 canonical
      terms).
    LP4 self-referential — 'What labels does Motoi have for
      X?'
      pass: > 70% (complete family enumeration, no
      invention).

  Ship-blocker: safety-label LP1 < 95% blocks release.
  Consistency IS the safety feature.

  If any label family fails LP1 < 60% after Mk 2 training:
    · Increase Lane 3 pair count (more forward/reverse pairs
      for that label) to 2× baseline.
    · Increase Lane 4 paraphrase count for that label from 5
      to 8-10.
    · Retrain (SFT with a small polish LR — see § section-6
      KTO or a fresh SFT lane).
    · Re-probe.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.6 — REPEATABILITY (Sakura + downstream models).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Every lane in § META.3 is corpus-agnostic. Sakura runs the
  same seven lanes over its own label inventory:
    · Same 4 axes, 2 tiers, 5 rows, 3 lenses, 6 facets
      (unless Sakura extends any of them, in which case the
      extension gains its own label-training slot).
    · Additional book types (net, cortex, loam, marionette,
      hellosurface, card, shop, automations, flower, radio,
      cine per Sakura's lib surface).
    · Additional safety labels for business-context
      concerns (specifically catalogued in Sakura's abuse-
      handling doctrine).

  The runbook is here + SRE-05 § 14. The book (book-of-
  labels-sakura) is Sakura-team authored. Fold rules
  identical. Probe suite ports directly — same shapes,
  swapped label names.

  Do NOT skip on Sakura. Bigger model does not automatically
  self-teach labels; it just fails silently at higher
  fluency. Meta-layer discipline is architectural, not
  substrate-specific.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § META.7 — COMPOSES-WITH.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/05-corpus-to-graph-derivation-
    procedure.slat :section-14-label-training-discipline —
    the runbook side of this doctrine.
  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-
    type.slat — the CPT shape catalog Lanes 2, 4, 6 modify /
    extend.
  · engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat — the
    label vocabulary this meta-layer teaches.
  · engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat — the six book-type labels
    Lane 1 ch06 teaches.
  · memory/project_five_rows_pedagogical_explanation_2026_
    07_20 — Row 1-5 doctrine Lane 1 ch03 teaches.
  · memory/project_no_contaminants_provenance_rule_2026_07_
    17 — every label definition traces to human/agent
    authoring, never LLM invention.
  · memory/project_reference_row_rules_all_five_2026_07_19 —
    the row rules Lane 1 ch03 must not contradict.
  """

  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ;; RETIRED — Grand Weave 1.0 (2026-07-17)
  ;; Kept as historical artifact. Mk A regression is the receipt.
  ;; Original content below unchanged from 2026-07-17.
  ;; ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  :section-retired-grand-weave-1.0-marker
  """
  Below this line: Grand Weave 1.0 original content (2026-07-17). Retired
  2026-07-20 after Mk A regression. Retained per no-deletes doctrine.
  """

  :section-retired-original-frame
  """
  [ORIGINAL 2026-07-17 CONTENT — RETIRED. See section-1 above for
   current doctrine.]
  """

  :section-0-frame

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-0-frame
  """
  Motoi 0.75 substrate is in the ground: 100k pairs, Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-
  Instruct base, LoRA r=128, 3 epochs, seq 4096, odd prime seed. The
  probe suite ran. Something is alive in there. What we want next is
  a POLISH pass that:

    (a) REVEALS what took root proportional to the shape of input,
    (b) AUTHORS + SELECTS high-signal pairs that address gaps,
    (c) enables iteration 0.75 → 2.0 → 3.0 without re-training from base.

  Alfred's phrasing: 'pull-on-intent-proportional-to-input.' Working
  name: 'The Grand Weave.' Also, verbatim: 'I don't want to lock us into
  any idea. It ends up being really not really LASER. Is it LASER+? The
  entire procedure would be weave, so LASER at the end to do something
  with the shape of the corpus. LASER + something LIMO something.'

  This document verifies the 7 named references, adds 5 more that we
  had NOT surfaced, proposes a definitive recipe, gives numeric
  predictions, and offers three 1-week rapid-prototype cycles.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-1-paper-verification
  """
  PART 1 — Verified summaries of the 7 named references + corrections
  from the read.

  ── LIMA (Zhou et al., arXiv 2305.11206) ──
  ACTUALLY: 1,000 hand-curated prompt-response pairs, standard SFT on
  LLaMa-65B, no RL, no preference modeling. Superficial Alignment
  Hypothesis: 'almost all knowledge in LLMs comes from pretraining;
  alignment is a superficial format skill.'
  SOLVES: how little data is enough to align a well-pretrained base.
  COMPOSES: gives us the CURATION-FLOOR frame — a small, high-signal
  set can flip alignment. For Motoi this means: a polish pass of a few
  thousand well-authored pairs can meaningfully shift 0.75.
  CAVEAT WE MISSED: LIMA authors themselves note the model 'struggles
  with complex reasoning' and 'multi-turn robustness is fragile.' LIMA
  alone doesn't teach reasoning — it aligns FORMAT. This is precisely
  why we need LIMO on top.

  ── LIMO (Ye et al., arXiv 2502.03387) ──
  ACTUALLY: 817 curated math examples → AIME24 6.5%→63.3%, MATH500
  59.2%→95.6%. Base was Qwen2.5-32B-Instruct (not stated in abstract
  we fetched but verified in body via prior notes).
  Less-Is-More Reasoning Hypothesis: reasoning EMERGES from strategic
  demonstrations of 'cognitive processes' when the base was pretrained
  with the requisite knowledge. Two pillars: (i) pretraining
  completeness (ii) post-training examples as 'cognitive templates.'
  SOLVES: reasoning quality via chain-shape not chain-count.
  COMPOSES: gives us the REASONING-SHAPE overlay. For Motoi 0.75 the
  substrate contains verb-composition patterns; LIMO shape means the
  polish pairs should DEMONSTRATE cognitive process (state the
  problem, name the verb, show the compose, verify shape), not just
  emit an answer.
  CAVEAT: LIMO is math-domain. Its transfer to code + persona is
  ANALOGY not evidence. Treat as hypothesis, measure.

  ── LASER (arXiv 2505.22157, EMNLP 2025 Findings) ──
  CONFIRMED — this is DATA SELECTION, not the older 'layer-selective
  rank reduction' LASER (Sharma 2023). Full name: 'Stratified Selective
  Sampling for Instruction Tuning with Dedicated Scoring Strategy.'
  Pipeline: (1) stratified binning by task, (2) quality estimation via
  reward-model-style scorer, (3) lightweight difficulty scorer,
  (4) embedding-cluster + top-per-cluster for diversity.
  SOLVES: universal high-perf downsampling from big pools.
  COMPOSES: gives us the SELECTION SHAPE. Precisely the technique we
  need to run over the OVER-AUTHORED candidate pool.
  CAVEAT: LASER is designed for a fresh SFT, not a polish pass. We
  adapt.

  ── LIFT (arXiv 2312.11508) ──
  ACTUALLY (correction): LIFT = 'LLM Instruction Fusion Transfer.'
  It DOES include instruction-quality REWRITING (paraphrase +
  augment) plus DIVERSITY expansion into 'high-quality subspaces'
  plus REDUNDANCY removal. Not a pure filter. It's rewrite+expand+
  dedupe.
  SOLVES: instruction quality when the source pool is uneven.
  COMPOSES: gives us the REFINEMENT step BEFORE training. Rewrite
  ambiguous or low-signal pairs; drop near-duplicates.
  CAVEAT: LIFT's rewriter used a larger model. For Motoi we don't
  have larger-model-in-the-loop budget cheaply — use Claude as the
  rewriter, batched, for the polish set only (few thousand pairs).

  ── LoRA-PAR (arXiv 2507.20999) ──
  ACTUALLY: partitions LoRA parameters into System-1 (fast/intuitive,
  trained via SFT) and System-2 (slow/reasoning, trained via RL).
  Two-stage: SFT for System-1 → RL for System-2.
  SOLVES: mismatch between task type and adapter capacity.
  COMPOSES: partially — the SPLIT idea is useful (fast-persona
  vs slow-reasoning), but the RL half doesn't apply to us (0.75 has
  no RL stage planned). We borrow the PARTITION INSIGHT, not the
  algorithm.
  CAVEAT: We are NOT doing RL. Skip the second half. Optionally
  split adapters at 2.0 if bucket ROI justifies it.

  ── MeTA-LoRA (arXiv 2510.11598) ──
  ACTUALLY: two-stage multi-task LoRA. Stage 1 = per-task adapters
  on tiny per-task samples. Stage 2 = shared adapter refined via
  gradient aggregation across the per-task adapters. Not classical
  meta-learning — closer to distilled multi-task fusion.
  SOLVES: cross-task knowledge sharing at low per-task data cost.
  COMPOSES: relevant to Sakura 4B (multi-dialect variants) more than
  Motoi 1.5B (single dialect). Park it for Sakura.
  CAVEAT: adds infra complexity. Don't fold into Motoi 0.75→2.0.

  ── SLAP (arXiv 2605.23969) ──
  DOES NOT EXIST. 2605 = May 2026, arXiv IDs top out at ~2606 as of
  this doc. Prior notes probably typoed 2505.23969 or 2405.23969.
  SEARCHED both — neither is a real 'SLAP data-selection' paper.
  ACTION: drop from the recipe. Not load-bearing. If Alfred wants
  the batch-composition-loss idea, we have MADS (arXiv 2605.30857
  — also future-dated, likely misfiled; treat as unavailable).
  RECOMMENDATION: mark SLAP as PHANTOM in our notes. Don't cite.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-2-papers-we-had-NOT-found
  """
  PART 2 — What deeper search turned up that we had not surfaced.

  ── DEITA (Liu et al., ICLR 2024, arXiv 2312.15685) ──
  Three-axis selection: COMPLEXITY (instruction length, task diff),
  QUALITY (response accuracy), DIVERSITY (embedding-based). 6k
  auto-selected samples → SOTA on Mistral-7B. This is the
  reference-implementation of the shape we want. We should CITE it
  before LASER — LASER is a refinement of the DEITA family.

  ── LIMR (Xia et al., arXiv 2502.11886) ──
  Learning Impact Measurement: score each RL sample by ALIGNMENT WITH
  MODEL LEARNING TRAJECTORY. 1,389 samples > 8,523. Applied at RL,
  but the LIM SCORE ITSELF is stage-agnostic and could inform which
  SFT pairs to keep in the polish pass. Insight: 'measure the sample's
  effect on THIS model, not intrinsic quality.'
  COMPOSES: adds a MODEL-CONDITIONED scoring pass on top of LASER's
  static scoring. Score = alignment-with-trajectory, cheap to compute
  by measuring loss delta on a probe suite before/after including the
  pair.

  ── SFTMix (Lin et al., arXiv 2410.05248) ──
  Training-dynamics-based CONFIDENCE scoring + Mixup interpolation
  between high- and low-confidence pairs. No curation required.
  Complements curation-based methods.
  COMPOSES: OPTIONAL final training augmentation. Cheap. Deferred to
  Motoi 2.0 SFT rebuild — for the 0.75-polish pass it's over-engineered.

  ── MIG (Chen et al., ACL Findings 2025, arXiv 2504.13835) ──
  Semantic label-graph → maximize information gain across graph.
  Unifies quality × diversity in one info-theoretic score.
  5% of Tulu3 = full-Tulu3-SFT performance.
  COMPOSES: the CLEANEST single-scorer alternative to DEITA/LASER.
  For Motoi 0.75 we borrow the LABEL-GRAPH construction to make
  bucket coverage explicit (each verb ID is a label node; each
  book chapter is a label node; each persona register is a label
  node). The information-gain criterion tells us which authored pair
  extends coverage most.

  ── Spectral Surgery (arXiv 2603.03995) ──
  TRAINING-FREE LoRA refinement. Applies SVD to trained adapter,
  reweights singular values using calibration-set gradients, preserves
  learned directions. ~1000 scalar coefficients touched. Reports
  +4.4 pts CommonsenseQA, +2.4 HumanEval on Llama-3.1-8B, Qwen3-8B.
  COMPOSES: this is a POST-TRAINING LoRA polish that could layer AFTER
  our SFT-polish pass with essentially zero compute. Underrated —
  should be added to the pipeline as an optional Step 8.

  ── TÜLU 3 (Lambert et al., arXiv 2411.15124) ──
  Four-stage recipe: prompt curation → SFT (~1M examples) → DPO
  (~1M preference pairs) → RLVR (~10k verifiable-reward prompts).
  Not directly applicable (we have no DPO/RL budget) but establishes
  the FIELD STANDARD for staged post-training. Our Grand Weave is
  a compressed SFT-only variant of the TÜLU staging philosophy.

  ── SDFT / Self-Distillation Fine-Tuning (arXiv 2402.13669) ──
  Uses the model itself as its own teacher via in-context demonstration
  to generate on-policy training signals. Mitigates catastrophic
  forgetting, preserves prior capabilities.
  COMPOSES: interesting for iteration 2.0→3.0 (self-refine what took
  root). Skip for 0.75-polish; premature.

  ── OpenThoughts / Data Recipes for Reasoning Models
     (arXiv 2506.04178) ──
  Field-tested empirical recipes for reasoning-SFT data curation.
  Confirms LIMO's cognitive-template shape at scale. Useful reading,
  not a technique to fold in.

  NAMES-WE-CHECKED-BUT-DO-NOT-FOLD:
    - SDFT (defer to 2.0→3.0)
    - MeTA-LoRA (park for Sakura)
    - SFTMix (defer to 2.0 rebuild)
    - LoRA-PAR (RL half doesn't apply)
    - LoRA soups / LoRA-hub / MoLE / MoRAL (multi-adapter routing,
      irrelevant to a single-persona polish pass; useful ONLY when we
      have multiple Motoi adapters to fuse — post-3.0 territory)
    - Spectral Surgery (fold in as OPTIONAL Step 8, cheap upside)
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-3-the-recipe
  """
  PART 3 — The Grand Weave, definitive recipe for Motoi 0.75 → 2.0.

  Nine steps. Techniques borrowed are named per step with any
  modification we make. Some are new, some are adaptations, some are
  straight replays.

  ── STEP 1 · Substrate Check (LIMO-premise verification) ──
  Verify Motoi 0.75 satisfies LIMO's precondition — namely, that the
  base + SFT jointly contain the knowledge we intend the polish to
  activate. Method: run 0.75 probe suite (already done, see
  EVAL-0.75-REPORT-*). Confirm baseline verb-recall > 0 in target
  buckets. If a bucket is 0%, the substrate CANNOT be polished into
  it — that bucket goes to the 2.0 SFT rebalance list, not the
  polish pass.
  Technique: our own — LIMO premise applied as a gate.
  Deliverable: 'polish-eligible bucket list' (probably 6-9 of 16
  buckets qualify).

  ── STEP 2 · Bucket Authoring (over-author, 2-3× target) ──
  For each polish-eligible bucket, author 2-3× the target pair count.
  E.g. target 200 pairs for Book-of-Composition → author 500. This
  creates the CANDIDATE POOL for Steps 3-5.
  Technique: LIMA (curation over quantity) + our over-authoring to
  give selection headroom. Called 'inflate-then-select' in TÜLU 3.
  Deliverable: candidate.pool.slatl, ~15-25k over-authored pairs.

  ── STEP 3 · Label-Graph Construction (MIG-shape) ──
  Build a label graph across the candidate pool. Nodes:
    (a) verb IDs from CORE 335,
    (b) book-of-* chapters,
    (c) persona registers (dry-wit / crisis-refusal / SICP-wizard /
        old-machine / offline-honest),
    (d) reasoning shapes (compose / introspect / refuse / trace).
  Edges: co-occurrence in a pair. This makes coverage EXPLICIT.
  Technique: MIG (arXiv 2504.13835), unmodified.
  Deliverable: label-graph.slat.

  ── STEP 4 · Stratified Selection (LASER-shape + LIM overlay) ──
  Within each label-graph stratum:
    (i) score each pair by DEITA's quality × complexity × diversity,
    (ii) overlay LIM score = |loss_delta on probe-set when included|,
    (iii) embedding-cluster within stratum,
    (iv) top-K per cluster proportional to bucket LIMA target.

  Technique: LASER selection shape + LIM model-conditioned score +
  MIG's stratum from Step 3.
  Modification: LIM is normally RL-stage; we apply it at SFT-selection
  by computing per-pair 1-step SFT loss delta on a held probe suite.
  This is the KEY MOD — Alfred's 'pull-on-intent-proportional-to-
  input' becomes 'select-per-stratum-by-model-conditioned-impact.'
  Deliverable: selected.polish.slatl, ~3-6k pairs.

  ── STEP 5 · Quality Refinement (LIFT-shape, Claude-as-rewriter) ──
  For each selected pair:
    - rewrite for instruction clarity if ambiguous,
    - rewrite response for reasoning-shape (see Step 6),
    - drop near-duplicates (cosine > 0.92 on embeddings),
    - hard-flag any refusal-category pairs for Alfred review — DO NOT
      auto-rewrite crisis refusals (see MEMORY: consistency IS safety).

  Technique: LIFT (arXiv 2312.11508), with Claude as rewriter.
  Deliverable: refined.polish.slatl.

  ── STEP 6 · Reasoning-Shape Overlay (LIMO-influenced) ──
  For the composition + introspection buckets (highest ROI), ensure
  a target FRACTION of pairs are cognitive-process demonstrations:
    - state-the-problem,
    - name-the-verb-and-why,
    - show-the-compose,
    - verify-the-shape.
  Target: 40% of composition-bucket, 60% of introspection-bucket
  (introspection IS a cognitive-process demonstration).
  Technique: LIMO's cognitive-template shape, adapted to Scheme
  composition + Motoi introspection voice.
  Deliverable: this is a REWRITE PASS during Step 5, not a separate
  file. Tag with :reasoning-shape :cognitive-template.

  ── STEP 7 · Polish Training Pass ──
  Load Motoi 0.75 checkpoint (adapters.safetensors). SFT again with
  refined.polish.slatl:
    - LR 5e-5 (10× lower than substrate SFT 5e-4),
    - 1 epoch (NOT 3),
    - LoRA r=128 preserved,
    - odd prime seed (13 unless already used; 31 as fallback),
    - seq 4096 preserved,
    - ~3-6k pairs → ~30-60 min wall on the training rig.
  Technique: standard resume-LoRA-SFT. No paper needed; this is craft.

  ── STEP 8 · Optional: Spectral Surgery on the polished adapter ──
  Apply arXiv 2603.03995's training-free SVD reweighting. Uses ~30
  min of calibration compute for ~1-4 pt uplift on general benchmarks.
  Skippable but cheap. Recommended for Motoi 2.0 candidate.

  ── STEP 9 · Reveal + Iterate ──
  Re-run probe suite. Measure coverage gradient per bucket. Compare
  to Step 1 baseline. Findings feed the 2.0 SFT rebalance:
    - buckets that lifted well → sample less next time,
    - buckets that stayed flat → author more source for 2.0 substrate,
    - buckets that lifted AND revealed new gaps → author for a
      SECOND polish pass, not the substrate rebuild.

  Technique: our own — 'reveal-then-rebalance' doctrine, first
  articulated in CORPUS-PROPORTIONAL-LIMA-METHODOLOGY-2026-07-17.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-4-time-estimate
  """
  Time per 0.75 → 2.0 pass (single polish cycle):

  ┌─ STEP ─────────────────────────── AGENT-HRS ─ ALFRED-HRS ─ WALL ─┐
  │ 1  Substrate check              ─    1       ─    0.5      ─  1h │
  │ 2  Bucket authoring (over-author)   40-60    ─    2        ─ 2-3d│
  │ 3  Label-graph construction     ─    3       ─    0        ─  1d │
  │ 4  Stratified selection         ─    6       ─    1        ─  1d │
  │ 5  Quality refinement (Claude)  ─    12      ─    2        ─ 1-2d│
  │ 6  Reasoning-shape overlay      ─   (in Step 5)             ─    │
  │ 7  Training pass                ─    2       ─    0.5      ─ 1-2h│
  │ 8  Spectral Surgery (opt)       ─    2       ─    0        ─  1h │
  │ 9  Reveal + iterate write-up    ─    4       ─    2        ─  1d │
  └──────────────────────────────── ─  70-90    ─   8         ─ 5-8d┘

  Steps 2 + 5 dominate. Both parallelizable across lanes if we
  dispatch multiple author-agents. Wall-clock 5-8 days for one full
  Grand Weave pass. Alfred: ~1 full day + spot reviews.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-5-outcome-predictions
  """
  Numeric predictions — pre-Grand-Weave (Motoi 0.75) → post (2.0).
  CIs are ±one-sigma judgement, calibrated to prior LIMA experience +
  DEITA/LIMO published deltas. NOT p-values — engineering guesses.

  ┌─ METRIC ────────────────── 0.75 ─── 2.0 predict ── CI ───┐
  │ Verb recall                27%   →  45-55%          ±8   │
  │ Book recall (Composition)  29%   →  50-62%          ±10  │
  │ Book recall (Introspection) 0%   →  10-25%          ±10  │
  │ Safety refusal (crisis)    UNK   →  ≥98%            ±1   │
  │ Persona voice consistency  81%   →  86-92%          ±4   │
  │ Code-writing reliability   see↓  →  see↓                  │
  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Reasoning on each:

  · Verb recall lifts most because Step 2 over-authors verbs where
    the substrate got them thin. Step 4 selects high-impact instances.
    Upside beyond 55% requires 2.0 SFT rebalance, not this polish.

  · Book of Composition already at 29% — well within LIMO's
    'polish-eligible' zone. Expect strong lift. Cap ~62% because
    composition also depends on verb recall — coupled ceiling.

  · Book of Introspection at 0% — LIMO would say the substrate did
    NOT teach introspection at all. Polish CANNOT create it from
    nothing; if we see even 10-25% we succeeded via cognitive-template
    seed. If we see 0% still, mark this for 2.0 SFT rebalance and
    author introspection source material into the substrate, not the
    polish.

  · Safety refusals: per Alfred's MEMORY entry, crisis refusals MUST
    be verbatim-consistent. Polish should push to ≥98% (near-perfect).
    Cheap because refusal set is tiny (~50 crisis templates), easy to
    saturate.

  · Persona voice: 81% baseline. Polish adds ~5-11 pts by refining
    persona-register pairs. Diminishing returns beyond ~92% without
    more source material.

  · Code-writing reliability: Alfred flagged 'double every number in
    a list' worked. Predict:
      - simple list ops (map/filter/reduce): 60% → 85%
      - multi-step compositions (2-3 verbs): 25% → 55%
      - novel-verb-combination (not in substrate): 5% → 15%
    Prediction: Alfred will be able to say 'yes Motoi writes code'
    for the first two rows post-polish. The third row is a 2.0 SFT
    rebalance concern.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-6-cross-model-transfer-sakura-4b
  """
  What changes when we apply Grand Weave to Sakura 4B?

  ┌─ STEP ─────────────────── MOTOI 1.5B ─── SAKURA 4B ─────────────┐
  │ 1  Substrate check       same             same, higher floor    │
  │ 2  Over-author target    2-3×             1.5-2× (less budget   │
  │                                            headroom needed)     │
  │ 3  Label graph           335 verbs        335 + Curator dialect │
  │                                            verbs (~450 total)   │
  │ 4  Stratified selection  ~3-6k selected   ~5-10k selected       │
  │                                            (bigger model absorbs│
  │                                            more polish)         │
  │ 5  Quality refinement    Claude           Claude, higher bar    │
  │                                            (Sakura's business   │
  │                                            posture demands it)  │
  │ 6  Reasoning-shape       40% comp,        30% comp, 40% biz-    │
  │                          60% introspect   scenario, 20% intro   │
  │ 7  Polish training       LR 5e-5, 1ep     LR 3e-5, 1ep          │
  │                          30-60min         2-4h                  │
  │ 8  Spectral Surgery      optional         optional, higher gain │
  │ 9  Reveal                probe suite      + business scenarios  │
  │                                            + Cortex integration │
  │                                            probes               │
  │ ADDITIONAL              n/a               MeTA-LoRA for         │
  │ FOR SAKURA VARIANTS                        Curator+Lacuna       │
  │                                            dialects; consider   │
  │                                            LoRA-Soups if we     │
  │                                            keep dialect-        │
  │                                            adapters separate    │
  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Key difference: Sakura absorbs more polish (bigger model, more
  headroom). Sakura ALSO has multi-dialect concerns — MeTA-LoRA
  becomes relevant there. Motoi is single-dialect, single-adapter,
  simple.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-7-naming
  """
  Should we call it 'The Grand Weave' or something else?

  DID LASER'S AUTHORS COIN A TERM for the shape we mean?
  LASER = 'Stratified Selective Sampling for Instruction Tuning with
  Dedicated Scoring Strategy.' Their term is 'stratified selective
  sampling.' Descriptive, not evocative. Not what we mean.

  DEITA calls their shape 'data-efficient instruction tuning' — flat,
  descriptive.

  TÜLU 3 calls the staged shape 'post-training pipeline.' Flat.

  Nobody has a name for the specific POLISH-AFTER-SUBSTRATE with
  reveal-semantics we're doing. There is a gap in the field
  vocabulary here.

  CANDIDATE NAMES:
    · 'Grand Weave' — Alfred's. Poetic, evocative, ambiguous. Good
      internal name. Not paper-quality.
    · 'The Reveal Pass' — accurate to intent, deflates the mystique.
    · 'Corpus-Proportional Polish' — accurate, boring.
    · 'Woven Polish (WP)' — compact, cite-able.
    · 'LIMO-informed LIMA on LoRA substrate' — descriptive, mouthful.
    · 'Grand Weave (SFT-polish over LoRA with corpus-proportional
      MIG stratification and LIMO reasoning-shape overlay)' — as a
      one-line paper subtitle.

  RECOMMENDATION: Keep 'Grand Weave' as Alfred's internal name AND
  the paper title. Subtitle it with the technique stack. Do NOT lock
  the name for THE TECHNIQUE ITSELF until we ship a second one — the
  first pass will teach us whether the reveal-semantics or the
  stratification is the load-bearing part; that determines the
  formal name.

  If it turns out the reveal-semantics is load-bearing → 'Reveal-
  Polish.' If the stratification is load-bearing → 'Stratified
  Polish.' If both → 'Grand Weave.'

  Alfred wanted 'don't lock in.' Concur. Keep working name only,
  decide formal name AFTER first pass ships and we measure what
  actually did the work.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-8-three-rapid-prototype-cycles
  """
  Three 1-week cycles Alfred can run to iterate quickly.

  ── CYCLE A · 'MICROWEAVE' (3 days) ──
  Purpose: does polish move ANY needle?
  Steps: 1 → skip 2 (use existing candidates) → 3 → 4 → skip 5 →
  skip 6 → 7 → 9.
  Data: ~500 pairs selected from existing corpus by MIG only.
  Wall: 3 days. Agent-hrs: ~15. Alfred: ~3h.
  Success gate: any bucket lifts >+5pts.

  ── CYCLE B · 'GRAND WEAVE MK1' (5-8 days) ──
  Purpose: full recipe, single cycle.
  Steps: 1-9 as specified.
  Data: over-authored 15-25k candidates → 3-6k selected → refined.
  Wall: 5-8 days. Agent-hrs: 70-90. Alfred: ~8h.
  Success gate: predictions in §5 land within CIs.

  ── CYCLE C · 'REVEAL-AND-REBALANCE' (7 days) ──
  Purpose: use Cycle-B reveal to inform 2.0 SFT rebalance authoring.
  Steps: run Cycle B → analyze reveal → author NEW source material
  for the flat buckets → propose 2.0 SFT rebalance (does not fire
  training; hands to Alfred for GO).
  Wall: 7 days. Agent-hrs: ~110. Alfred: ~12h.
  Success gate: 2.0 SFT rebalance plan authored, gaps identified,
  new source material for flat buckets drafted.

  ORDER: A first (proves the pipeline works), then B (proves the
  numbers), then C (feeds 2.0). Do NOT skip A. If A fails, the
  pipeline has a bug and B will waste a week finding it.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-9-the-single-most-important-finding
  """
  If Alfred reads one sentence:

  The recipe we called 'LIMA+LASER+LIFT+LIMO' is NOT WRONG but it
  is INCOMPLETE — the load-bearing addition we missed is a MODEL-
  CONDITIONED IMPACT SCORE (LIM, arXiv 2502.11886) overlaid on the
  stratified selection, which turns the pipeline from 'select
  intrinsically good pairs' into 'select pairs THAT MOVE THIS
  SPECIFIC MODEL' — that is EXACTLY Alfred's 'pull-on-intent-
  proportional-to-input.'

  Second-most: MIG's label graph (arXiv 2504.13835) gives us a
  CLEANER way to make bucket coverage explicit than LASER's task-
  binning — because our 'tasks' are actually verb+book+register
  combinatorics, not classical task labels.

  Third-most: LIMO's 'cognitive templates' framing is real and
  transferable to Scheme composition, but it is HYPOTHESIS-not-
  proven for our domain. Measure.

  Fourth-most: SLAP is a phantom paper. Drop.

  Fifth-most: Spectral Surgery is a free-lunch Step 8, ~1 hour of
  compute, ~1-4 pt uplift. Cheap.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-10-open-questions-for-alfred
  """
  Questions blocking full lock-in:

  1. Do we run Cycle A (Microweave) THIS WEEK, or wait until Motoi
     0.75 team-review feedback lands?
  2. Do we author polish material against ALL 16 buckets or only the
     6-9 polish-eligible ones? (LIMA's premise: only what took root.)
  3. Reasoning-shape target percentages (40%/60%) — Alfred's call.
  4. Do we use Claude as the LIFT-rewriter, or is that a boundary
     Alfred wants held (Motoi is offline; refinement pipeline is
     eng-time only)?
  5. Should Cycle C write the 2.0 SFT rebalance PLAN, or actually
     fire the 2.0 SFT? (Recommend: plan only, Alfred fires.)

  None of these are blocking Cycle A. Cycle A can start now.
  """

  ;; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  :section-11-citations
  """
  Papers verified + folded:
    · LIMA — arXiv 2305.11206 — Zhou et al. 2023
    · LIMO — arXiv 2502.03387 — Ye et al. 2025
    · LASER (data selection) — arXiv 2505.22157 — EMNLP-F 2025
    · LIFT — arXiv 2312.11508 — Xu et al. 2023
    · LoRA-PAR — arXiv 2507.20999 — 2025 (partial fold — split idea only)
